<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 18 日星期二 15:58:27 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Will Donald Trump Ever Go to Prison?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位前总统表示，他预计将再次被司法部起诉，这次的指控与 1 月 6 日有关。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/EXUymmeWjevA4iV9mqdMuumPbTM=/0x66:3514x2043/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1439325943/original.jpg" alt="唐纳德·特朗普戴着 MAGA 帽子的照片" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>赢得麦克纳米/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>尽管唐纳德·特朗普有时被称为“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bostonglobe.com/2023/04/04/opinion/another-teflon-don-finally-gets-scratched-court/">特氟隆唐</a>”——这个标签不仅与他自己的名字有关，而且与<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2018/08/trump-gravano-gotti-mafia/568273/">他的作案手法</a>有关——但事实并不是他逃脱了一切后果，而是他最令人震惊的行为。他曾<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/e-jean-carroll-verdict/674001/">在诽谤案中败诉</a>，他的公司因<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/09/ny-attorney-general-trump-organization-was-fraud/671500/">逃税</a>而受到指责，他还被指控犯<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-indictment-arrignment-speech/673616/">有错综复杂的商业犯罪</a>。但他犯下的最大罪行——尤其是试图窃取 2020 年总统选举的胜利——却没有受到惩罚。<br><br>这种模式可能很快就会被打破。特朗普<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://truthsocial.com/@realDonaldTrump/posts/110735295720085796">今天早上发表声明</a>称，他周日晚上收到了司法部特别顾问杰克·史密斯的一封“ <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.justice.gov/archives/jm/criminal-resource-manual-160-sample-target-letter">目标信</a>”。他说史密斯给了他四天的时间向大陪审团报告，调查特朗普试图颠覆 2020 年大选和 2021 年 1 月 6 日国会大厦骚乱。此类信件通常是起诉书的前奏。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：文书工作的妙招</a><br><br>特朗普并不是最可靠的消息来源。他是个顽固的骗子，三月份错误地声称他即将在纽约的一桩案件中被捕——事实证明，他被捕了，但直到一段时间后才被捕。尽管如此， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/live/2023/07/18/us/trump-jan-6-letter#trump-jan-6-letter">一些</a>媒体已经从其他消息<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/special-counsel-informs-trump-target-probe-efforts-overturn/story?id=101404037">来源</a>证实特朗普收到了这封信，而且这一消息与史密斯调查的已知情况相符。<br><br>如果可以合理地假设特朗普确实可能被指控犯有与 1 月 6 日相关的罪行，那么这仍然留下了很大的疑问。其中最重要的是这些可能是什么犯罪。传闻中的可能性包括<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/04/12/trump-fundraising-fraud-special-counsel/">筹款违规</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/28/us/politics/jan-6-prosecutors-trump-fund-raising.html">电汇欺诈</a>等检方惯用手段，甚至叛乱——这是一种极其罕见的指控，但众议院调查委员会 1 月 6 日将一项指控<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/january-6-committee-criminal-referral-donald-trump/672514/">提交</a>给了司法部。<br><br>史密斯可以选择对<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/12/trumps-coup-before-january-6/620998/">文件政变</a>的许多参与者提出广泛的指控，这将是一个更复杂的案件，但很可能会被定罪，或者他可以更狭隘地关注特朗普或一小部分助手，这可能是一个情况更简单，但在政治上更具煽动性。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：唐纳德·特朗普可能即将被起诉的指南</a><br><br>特朗普发现自己<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/01/indictment-donald-trump-fulton-georgia-mar-a-lago-documents-january-6/672800/">在全国各地的司法管辖区陷入了法律麻烦</a>，以至于他的律师上周在要求联邦法院推迟对机密文件处理不当的审判时引用了这些麻烦。 （史密斯上个月在该案中起诉了特朗普。）在曼哈顿，这位前总统面临的指控主要是向一名自称与他发生性关系的成人电影演员支付封口费。人们普遍预计佐治亚州富尔顿县地方检察官将在 8 月的某个时候提出与 2020 年选举相关的指控。<br><br>这些案件可以沿着两个轴绘制：定罪概率和犯罪严重性。犯罪就是犯罪，但曼哈顿案相对来说是小事，一些法律观察家认为检方的法律理论值得怀疑。文件案不仅非常严重——它涉及一些对国家安全最敏感的材料——而且事实相对简单，对特朗普来说也是毁灭性的。富尔顿县案件很严重，因为它涉及颠覆选举的企图，但也仅限于佐治亚州的行动；降低定罪的可能性具有挑战性。<br><br>但与 1 月 6 日相关的潜在联邦案件可能是最重要的案件。这些罪行再严重不过了：特朗普首先通过法律和政治计划，然后更绝望地通过武力来挫败选民的意愿。从来没有哪位总统如此直接地攻击美国民主的基础。相比之下，即使是尼克松的罪行也显得黯然失色。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：特朗普为避免起诉而进行的最后一搏</a><br><br>通俗地说，特朗普显然有罪。每个人都看着他声称他赢得了一场他没有赢得的选举。他们听到他向包括佐治亚州议员布拉德·拉芬斯佩格在内的官员施压，要求为他争取选票。他们听说他在 1 月 6 日煽动骚乱。他的行为非常恶劣，以至于众议院对他进行了弹劾，大多数参议员，包括一些共和党人，投票判定有罪——尽管仍低于定罪所需的三分之二。<br><br>然而，有些事情可能用普通话来说是明显正确的，但仍然具有挑战性或无法向陪审团证明。 “你和我都知道，这不是秘密，但在法庭上，在有争议的听证会上，用可接受的证据，排除合理怀疑来证明这一点要困难得多，”前联邦检察官保罗·罗森茨威格(Paul Rosenzweig)早些时候告诉我今年。二月，特朗普发布了一份备忘录<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/02/trump-january-6-possible-indictment-defense-jack-smith/673070/">，列出了他可能对与骚乱相关的任何指控进行辩护的理由</a>。在今天的声明中，他将针对他的案件描述为“选举干涉”，这是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/10/trump-calls-china-interfere-2020-election/599365/">“我是橡皮，你是胶水</a>”肆无忌惮的惊人例子。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/trump-indictment-unsealed/674353/">大卫·A·格雷厄姆：可以想象到的最愚蠢的犯罪</a><br><br>政治敏感性也是不可避免的。无论史密斯指控什么，这都将是史无前例的。特朗普将在选举期间对这些指控提出异议。他的律师已经在寻求将文件案的审判<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trump-wants-use-his-campaign-escape-prosecution/674672/">推迟到 2024 年大选之后</a>，如果他获胜，他很可能能够命令司法部结案。<br><br>所有这些因素意味着没有人可以自信地预测定罪，更不用说监禁了。但与 1 月 6 日相关的目标信将是追究特朗普对美国的罪行负责的首批具体步骤之一。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 15:15:07 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/trumps-january-6-target-letter-jack-smith/674738/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Root Cause of the Homelessness Crisis]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/9xDFDUsEn1ZSw2w_-GO9zCLrUzg=/0x24:4799x2723/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_1238537050/original.jpg" alt="2022 年 2 月 16 日，加利福尼亚州洛杉矶市中心附近，收容无家可归者的帐篷在关闭的店面前排成一排。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>弗雷德里克·J·布朗/法新社/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>美国 30% 的无家可归者和 50% 的无家可归者居住在加利福尼亚州，总数超过 170,000 人。无家可归<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2023/01/homelessness-affordable-housing-crisis-democrats-causes/672224/">主要是更广泛的住房负担能力危机的结果</a>，而这又主要是地方政府在最需要的地方建造新住房的难度的结果。<br><br> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/BenBayer/status/1634194893579984900?s=20">专家</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://reason.com/podcast/2022/01/12/michael-shellenberger-how-progressives-ruined-american-cities/">政客</a>经常声称，加州无家可归危机实际上是人们为了更好的天气或更好的公共福利而离开其他州的结果。但新的研究对这一理论提出了质疑。上个月，加州大学旧金山分校的研究人员发布了 25 年来最大规模的无家可归者代表性调查。它包含来自加州 3,200 名无家可归者的调查数据以及对其中 300 多名无家可归者的深入采访。<br><br>接受调查的无家可归者绝大多数是当地人，而不是来自远方的移民：90% 的人失去了在加利福尼亚州的最后一个住房，75% 的人在他们经历无家可归的同一县失去了它。在 10% 来自其他地方的人中，30% 出生在加利福尼亚州。其他大多数人都有家庭或雇佣关系，或者以前曾在该州居住过。<br><br>退一步来说，数以万计的人在无家可归后搬到加州的想法毫无意义。搬家很贵。失去住房的人很少有办法在全国范围内运送自己、家人、宠物和财物。抛开这一点不谈，无家可归使人们变得脆弱。第一本能不是搬到新的地方，而是留在家人和朋友网络以及潜在的工作机会附近。<br><br>研究人员小心翼翼地确定受访者的来源，但没有促使他们给出任何一个答案。 “我们没有说，‘嘿，你来自加利福尼亚州吗？’”该研究的首席研究员、贝尼奥夫无家可归者和住房计划主任玛戈特·库谢尔告诉我。她说，受访者被要求回顾他们的生活史，解释导致他们无家可归的情况。在此过程中，他们被要求澄清关键的地理细节。<br><br>例如，这是她与我分享的一次交流：<br><br><p>采访者：那你当时（第一次失去住房）几岁？</p><p>回答者：我33岁了。</p><p>采访者：三十三，好吧。那是在这儿，还是在哪儿？</p><p>受访者：那实际上是在加利福尼亚州的波莫纳。</p><p>采访者：波莫纳，好的。然后你一直呆在那里吗？你无家可归之后发生了什么？你的转变是什么？</p><p>受访者：嗯，我有点跳来跳去，但在地理位置上并不是很多。我有点摇摆不定，只是因为，就像我说的，我根本不知道如何应对无家可归的情况。我以前从未无家可归过。我感觉不舒服。我正在努力寻找睡觉的地方。每次他们把你赶走时，你都会说：“好吧，我不能睡在那里，所以我就去这里吧。”所以，事情就是这样发生的。我最终来到了一个叫克莱蒙特的城市……还有另一个克莱蒙特实际上就在波莫纳附近。这就是我住的地方，在波莫纳和克莱蒙特、安大略省、奇科等地区之间来回穿梭。它的地理面积不是很大，但技术上是不同的城市。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：您[无家可归]之前住在哪里？</p><p>受访者：加利福尼亚州圣贝纳迪诺。我妈妈的房子有五间卧室。她在那里住了50年零14天。</p><p>采访者：你妈妈的房子，好吧。你离开那所房子回到这里。</p><p>对方：就走开了。</p><p>记者：是因为她去世了吗？</p><p>受访者：不，因为我的家人很恶魔而且很可怕。我们应该哀悼她，而他们只是来看看能从房子里得到什么和其他东西。所以，我就离开了，因为事情不应该是这样的。我哥哥因为照顾我妈妈、殴打我等等而让我住院三次。我原谅他们；我想继续前进。无家可归只是一个停留；你给汽车充电，充电，然后重新上路。我生命中最美好的部分就是我生命的下一部分。就是这样。</p>这是另一个：<br><br><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到这里的？那么你在德克萨斯州；你有房子。</p><p>回答者：我有房子。我得了癌症，肾癌。我失去了工作，失去了房子……</p><p>采访者：你在休斯顿做什么——什么样的工作？</p><p>受访者：我当了20年卡车司机。</p><p>采访者：那你是怎么来到加州的呢？</p><p>受访者：我来自加利福尼亚州。于是我就回到了家。</p>加利福尼亚州是大多数无家可归者的<em>家园</em>。最常报告的失去住房的原因是由于失业或工作时间减少而导致收入减少。其次是经济原因，其次是两个社会原因：居民之间的冲突，以及对室友或家庭成员施加压力的担忧。在一个更负担得起的环境中，这些社会原因只会导致地址的改变，而不是无家可归。<br><br>通过提前识别高危人群来防止无家可归是非常困难的。部分原因是，处于不稳定局势中的人们比真正失去家园的人们要大得多，而且正如报告所揭示的那样，当人们确实失去家园时，这种情况发生得非常快。签订租约的受访者平均提前 10 天收到他们将失去住房的通知。 60% 没有租约的人报告中位数只有一天。这并不是联系社会服务机构寻求帮助的宽限期。<br><br>然而库舍尔强调，一些无家可归的现象是可以预见的。许多人因监狱或看守所而变得无家可归——占受访者的 19%。更重要的是，67% 的受访者入狱时无家可归。然而，只有不到 20% 的人表示在退出时获得了福利、医疗保健或住房支持。库舍尔表示，阻止加州新一轮无家可归者的流动是“轻而易举的事”：“我们知道人们在哪里；我们知道他们会发生什么。”<br><br>一旦人们失去了家园，搬进新家就变得极具挑战性。受访者表示，距离上次拥有住房的时间中位数为 22 个月。近 90% 的受访者表示，住房成本影响了他们摆脱无家可归的能力。一位受访者表示：“我曾尝试自己寻找公寓，但我想确保自己能买得起。而他们中的大多数人，他们想要三倍的租金。仅就单间公寓或一间卧室而言，价格为 1,100 美元、1,200 美元，仅此而已。我说，‘哇’，你知道吗？这意味着我必须赚到 3,300 美元。我并没有这么做。而且我不会很快做到这一点。”<br><br>超过一半的受访者表示，他们<em>能</em>负担得起的住房距离工作或医疗保健太远，不安全，没有公共交通服务，或者距离孩子或家人太远。受访者还提到了住房歧视、在寻找合适的经济适用住房方面缺乏支持、住房等待时间长达数年、缺乏住房券以及药物滥用（包括在街上使用药物保持清醒和警惕）等障碍。<br><br>无家可归就像慢慢地从山上滚下来。在某人跌倒（或失去住房）后立即是提供帮助的最佳时机：在他们经历创伤和不稳定事件<em>之前</em>。在他们出现或恶化药物滥用问题<em>之前</em>。在他们用尽家人和朋友愿意提供的所有帮助<em>之前</em>。在他们上班迟到太多次，或者没有干净衣服上班<em>之前</em>。<br><br>但即使是一个运作良好、资金充足、及早干预的无家可归机构也无法结束无家可归危机，因为无家可归危机就是<em>家庭</em>危机。<br><br>对于即将从与大家庭共同居住的过度拥挤的公寓中被驱逐的人来说，房屋的中位价意味着什么？实际上很多。一条住房链连接着低收入住房、中等收入住房和高收入住房。当新的市场价格单位首次推出并且人们搬进其中时，这会释放他们以前居住的房屋（通常较旧）的空间。当新住房<em>没有</em>投放市场时，高收入居民就会转向旧住房，从而抬高价格。反过来，中等收入工人转向低收入住房单元，底层的每个人都挤在数量不断减少的经济适用房中，直到有人失去自己的位置。<br><br>加州和全国其他昂贵的州推迟建造更多住房的每一天，都会有一个未来的家庭流落街头。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 13:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/california-homeless-housing-crisis/674737/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[How to Redeem Social Media]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>下一代平台不必犯与上一代平台相同的错误。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/H_vof0lqGCujdBkZHC3jWaNNkI4=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/building_back_social_media_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="巨大的岩石拇指，里面长出一朵花" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>本·科特/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure> Twitter 的缓慢崩溃激发了许多潜在的继任者的灵感。数百万人正在尝试新的社交媒体平台，例如 Meta 的 Threads，热情战胜了经验。<em>我确信，为一个不负责任的亿万富翁运营的社交媒体平台创建免费内容，这次会产生不同的结果</em>，我们告诉自己，就好像我们都是昨天出生的一样。<br><br>我们知道这个故事的结局。我们知道，Facebook 和 Twitter 等平台一开始是令人愉快的联系和对话场所，然后分裂成由可疑病毒内容主导的超极化亚文化，党派成员在各自对立的回声室中互相尖叫。过去如此，将来也将如此。<br><br>除非社交媒体公司有意识地决定以不同的方式做事。这个过渡时刻也是一个机遇时刻，他们有机会重新构想社交媒体的面貌。 Threads 和 Bluesky 等新平台仍在建设中，这意味着它们仍然会受到影响，社会的选择仍然是开放的。这些网站不必复制以前的内容，并且可以从过去的错误中吸取教训。较旧的平台依靠煽动性参与来提高短期利润，但这种选择最终从内部破坏了社交网络，疏远了用户和广告商。如今的平台可以通过旨在建立信任而不是削弱信任的新规则和功能来吸引下一代用户，从而确保网站的长期生存能力。<br><br>以下是我自己的一些建议。该清单并不详尽，理性的人无疑会不同意其中的一些建议。但我希望我们都能同意这次对话的必要性，以及在再次拥抱社交媒体之前重新思考我们想要从社交媒体中得到什么的必要性。<br><br>制定道路规则。<br><br>多年来，Facebook 允许否认大屠杀<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2020/10/12/923002012/facebook-bans-holocaust-denial-reversing-earlier-policy">——直到它不再这样做</a>。几个月来，Twitter <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://reason.com/2023/01/02/under-government-pressure-twitter-suppressed-truthful-speech-about-covid-19/">一直在压制</a>一系列有关 COVID-19 的言论——有些是虚假的，有些只是有争议的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/2022/11/29/1139822833/twitter-covid-misinformation-policy-not-enforced">——直到它不再出现为止</a>。这两个平台都禁止了唐纳德·特朗普，然后又改变了方向。与此同时，那些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/zlj517/status/1238111898828066823">暗示</a>COVID-19 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/SpokespersonCHN/status/1258780531707109377">起源</a>于美国并试图<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.propublica.org/article/how-china-uses-youtube-and-twitter-to-spread-its-propaganda-version-of-life-for-uyghurs-in-xinjiang">掩盖</a>其政权对维吾尔穆斯林的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/the-uyghur-chronicles/">可怕镇压的</a>中国官员大多都没有受到惩罚。问题不在于 Twitter 或 Facebook 等社交媒体公司对其内容进行了审核。问题在于他们的流程不透明且看似反复无常，而且决策的确切依据很少向公众披露。这种专断的管理非但没有培育出健康的在线社区，反而滋生了不信任。<br><br>相反，我们需要的是一套透明的、详细的标准来管理停职、禁令和其他惩罚，这些标准必须得到明确解释、定期更新和一致应用。社交媒体平台通常会将这些决定的具体细节保密，因为他们希望避免引发争议。但将审核变成黑匣子却引发了另一种形式的争议。由于用户永远无法确切地知道为什么某些内容被删除或压制，这些平台很容易成为怀疑、偏执和偏见指控的目标。确实，没有一套公共节制原则能让所有人满意。但这是一个功能，而不是一个错误。用户将可以根据平台是否符合自己的理想来选择把时间花在哪里，平台将不再被用户不断抱怨自己的待遇所困扰。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/03/social-media-algorithms-twitter-meta-rss-reader/673282/">Yair Rosenberg：如何重新控制您在互联网上阅读的内容</a><br><br><strong>拥抱无常和隐私。</strong><br><br>现实世界的对话和社交媒体互动的区别在于，网络版本是永恒的，这使得个人很难超越过去的自己和最愚蠢的言论。年轻人尤其容易在网上过度分享，常常表现出他们与年龄相称的无知和不成熟。在互联网出现之前，随着一个人进入成年期，青春期的这一自然部分就会逐渐消失。然而如今，情况已不再如此，并带来了不良后果——而且不仅仅是对青少年而言。在极端情况下，网络攻击考古学家会挖掘人们的个人资料，寻找他们多年前发表的有问题的言论，无论这些情绪是否反映了这个人现在是谁。这创造了一种持续监视和怀疑的文化，并有可能<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/63399d48fb1fdd0036293c1e/yom-kippur-forgiveness-anti-semitism-antepli/">将有前途的人囚禁</a>在最糟糕的版本中，永远因他们最早的错误而蒙上污点。<br><br>为了防止这些问题，平台应该默认存档旧内容，并在一段设定的时间（也许是 30 天）后让其他人无法访问这些内容，该时间可以由用户调整。旧帖子对于那些制作它们的人来说仍然是可读的，但对于陌生人和搜索引擎来说却无法访问。社交媒体可能再次成为一种对话，评论不再被理解为个人对某个主题的最后一句话，而是作为一个人不断进化的一部分。尽管这项政策可能允许一些杰出人物归档他们过去不那么令人愉快的部分，但对于那些不应该陷入最低谷的普通人来说，这种成本所带来的好处超过了这一成本。<br><br><strong>结束趋势。</strong><br><br>过去一周，“犹太人”一直是推特上的热门话题。这并不是因为人们钦佩他们对美国冰淇淋行业<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.timesofisrael.com/the-jewish-history-of-americas-most-famous-ice-creams/">的巨大贡献</a>。这是因为极右帐户一直在分享反犹太主义内容。公众对犹太人的好色迷恋早在社交媒体之前就已经存在，但定期在侧边栏上展示它是一种选择。 Twitter 的“趋势”部分旨在捕捉用户当前正在讨论的所有内容，但在实践中，它常常放大了平台的病态，将用户引导至病毒式传播和人为加剧的骗局。<br><br>这些问题可以通过人为调节得到部分改善，但这需要人力和文化能力，而且这些决定会不断引发争议。赢得这场游戏的唯一方法就是不玩，让用户谈论他们喜欢的内容，而不刺激他们进行不相关的对话或激励追逐潮流的内容。在线激进主义也将摆脱主题标签活动的怪异控制，这些活动以其知名度吸引了组织，但不一定能带来回报。<br><br><strong>禁止世界领导人，或者至少禁止本国人民使用社交媒体的领导人。</strong><br><br>无论是特朗普煽动国会大厦骚乱，还是伊朗最高领袖一边<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/khamenei_ir/status/446928689943420928?lang=fi">否认</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/khamenei_ir/status/1321494146989907969">大屠杀</a>一边<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Yair_Rosenberg/status/1534560786462416897">煽动</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/Yair_Rosenberg/status/1552450234210459650">反犹太主义</a>，国家元首往往是社交媒体平台最头疼的问题。由于这些人的言论本质上具有新闻价值，因此即使他们最极端的言论受到缓和也会带来问题，无论他们的话的潜在后果有多么危险。正如特朗普的例子所表明的那样，有关政治领导人的具体决定会受到指控和争议，并且不可避免地会在平台上遭到反击。解决方案是首先不要让他们进入网站。这些政客并不是缺乏其他传达信息的选择。更重要的是，让他们远离社交媒体也会产生有益的效果，鼓励他们为自己的实际选民工作，而不是为无定形的在线观众表演。你可以担任总统，也可以担任总统，但不能两者兼而有之。<br><br> <a href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/62a11ef0582ffb002082bd49/iran-ayatollah-ali-khamenei-twitter-anti-semitism/">Yair Rosenberg：为什么 Twitter 不会禁止其最强大的反犹太分子</a><br><br>一个不太雄心勃勃的选择是：如果一个国家限制其公民使用社交媒体网站，则应禁止其政治领导人和外交官使用该平台。目前，中国和伊朗的独裁政权封锁了本国人民的脸书和推特，同时允许本国官员使用这些平台进行宣传。实际上，这意味着独裁政权能够在社交媒体上为自己的人民说话，而面临的反对最小。展望未来，平台应该让一个国家的官员遵守这些官员对他们镇压的人民施加的相同标准。<br><br>社交媒体<span class="smallcaps"> </span>就被强加给我们的社会，而没有对其影响进行任何深思熟虑。它产生了许多积极的影响，提高了以前闻所未闻的声音并揭露了不公正现象。但它也使我们的集体话语<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/05/social-media-democracy-trust-babel/629369/">变得粗俗</a>，使我们对复杂问题的讨论变得愚蠢，并培育了一种阴谋主义和持续争议的文化。其中许多失败都是人类的失败，但第一波社交媒体网站的结构<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/elon-musk-twitter-problems-misinformation-bigotry/671952/">加剧了这些失败并奖励了</a>它们。<br><br>最终，这些失败导致了平台的退化，这意味着缓解这些问题符合下一代社交媒体公司的最佳利益。当这些网站首次推出时，它们的所有者并不知道他们会与总统和流行病发生争执。现在他们做到了，是时候吸取过去几十年的教训来重建他们的基础设施了。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/twitter-threads-new-suggested-rules/674709/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[In Praise of Phone Numbers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>互联网提供了许多新的沟通方式，但没有什么比 10 位数的电话号码更重要的了。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/a52YFmgtdZ3O1Ip79Zxz6dKtA6E=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/phone_numbers/original.png" alt="一只手拿着手机" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/《大西洋月刊》插图</figcaption></figure>想象一下一种简单、通用且无需软件更新的技术。它是一串数字，每个部分都充当一组精确的坐标 - 如此基本和优雅，以至于您的曾祖父母可以使用它。将数字按正确的顺序排列，这项技术就会立即触发一点魔力：几秒钟前还一片寂静，触觉上一片空白，突然之间，数英里甚至是大陆之外，突然爆发出一阵美妙的声音或振动。然后，如果你幸运的话，你会听到一个声音，然后你用你的声音回应：你的问题，你沮丧地请求与“代表”交谈！<br><br>自 1879 年以来，电话号码一直以某种形式存在于我们身边，与复写纸、VHS 磁带和随身听不同，它尚未过时。尽管现在有数十种联系方式，但很少有像拿起电话一样持久可靠。一个快速的思维实验：假设你刚刚遭遇了车祸，或者，上帝保佑，发现自己真的处于紧急情况——你会发短信寻求帮助，还是会拨打紧急联系人或 911？尽管我们的大部分身份已经转移到网上，但这些数字序列是与物理世界的模拟联系。当我们创建帐户或需要向任何给定的机器和网络系统证明我们的身份时，我们使用数字字符串作为身份验证手段。<br><br>但电话号码不仅是技术领域的自耕农——一种谦虚、实用的主力——它也是一块重要的文化试金石。我一直是一个没有国家的人；由于童年时的搬迁和成年后普遍的不安，他有幸收养了许多家乡，从曼哈顿到蒙大拿州的米苏拉。尽管我在徘徊，但我的地方感和我身份的一个重要方面却永远固定下来，这要归功于三个简单的号码： <em>610</em> ，这是“费城郊区”的总机电话<em>。</em> “我在那里只住了十年，但就是在那时我碰巧得到了我的第一部手机。因此，我的区号为我提供了类似于巧妙伪装甚至护照的东西。偶然发现另一个 610 号码就像打开一扇门一样。<em>你来自哪个城镇？噢，真的，你在哪里上学？</em>三位数可以把陌生人变成同路人。<br><br>电话号码，太棒了！一个伟大的发明，十分之十，没有注释！<em>打电话给 JG 温特沃斯！ 877-立即现金！ 800-588-2300，帝国（今天）！</em>如果没有电话号码我们会在哪里？无聊的？丢失的？穿着缠腰布，在明火上烤新鲜猎取的肉？ 2003 年的一天，我无意中走出了一个热门话题，走进普鲁士国王购物中心的一家 Cingular Wireless 商店，看到了一个几乎是随机的 10 位数指示符，这让我不禁感到有点浪漫。我仍然习惯在凌晨 1 点登录我的银行，联系兽医，并在我的群聊中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/realteaemoji/status/1679173275002322972?s=20">发送令人不安的人工智能生成的 TikTok</a> ，这就是持久力<em>和</em>多功能性。<br><br>在我 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/cwarzel/status/1641161893904793600">发布</a>关于电话号码在我们生活中所扮演的角色的推文后，许多人回复并分享了他们自己的观点。电话号码可以标志着一个新的场合，就像一位名叫 Austin McKinley 的用户所做的那样，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thebadcode/status/1641514561009483776?s=20">告诉</a>我，他 2008 年搬到旧金山时做的第一件事就是购买一部 iPhone 并获得一个本地电话号码。 “旧的生活结束了，新的生活开始了，”他写道。在缅因州（以及我以前的蒙大拿州）等地方，区号可能意味着国家自豪感。 “拥有非 207 号码是局外人的直接信号，”推特用户、迈纳州人本·斯普拉格 (Ben Sprague) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/bensprague/status/1641167129645809664?s=20">告诉</a>我。 “那些远离区号歧视的人有祸了。”一个好的号码也可以是与过去的情感纽带，因为它适用于一位位于费城、名叫艾米的用户，她<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/theHollandaise/status/1641164293746958336?s=20">告诉</a>我，她在母亲去世时继承了她的号码。我的朋友约翰在推特上的昵称是约翰尼·勇气（Johnny Courage），他写道，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/johnnycourage/status/1641296385361301504?s=20">保留</a>了自己的 919 区号，以“保持我在卡罗来纳州的真诚和南方侨民身份”。 “当然，这是昨天的古雅遗迹。但它把我和家联系在一起。”<br><br>这些老式的乐趣并不意味着电话号码没有随着时间的推移而演变。正如我的同事梅根·加伯 (Megan Garber) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">在 2014 年所写的那样</a>，电话号码最初是服务于较小地理区域的特殊字母数字地址（例如，她写道，MU 5-9975 会将您引导至总机代理，然后由该代理将您与纽约市默里山 (Murray Hill) 社区）。随着电话越来越普及，手动总机系统变得自动化，号码系统从地区性转向全国性，号码组更长，并引入了区号。每次编号系统扩展时，我们都会抱怨，但它仍然持续存在——北美当前的 10 位编号系统于 1997 年在马里兰州<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/23/technology/the-10-or-11-digit-local-call-fosters-anxiety-and-shrugs.html">推出</a>，我们没有回头。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/02/our-numbered-days-the-evolution-of-the-area-code/283803/">阅读：区号的演变</a><br><br>但即使是 10 位数字系统（我生活中的技术常数之一）也有过期日期。在某些时候，这些数字将会耗尽，这一认识让我想知道谁（如果有人）在密切关注我们的数字。值得庆幸的是，<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nationalnanpa.com/about_us/index.html">北美编号计划管理员（North American Numbering Plan Administrator）</a>是一个令人愉快的官僚组织，负责管理和分配 20 个国家/地区的电话号码和区号。假设一大群人搬到蒙大拿州或缅因州并申请新号码，NANPA 的高级主管 Florence Weber 告诉我，NANPA 的团队与运营商和州委员会合作推出新的区号，这个过程至少需要三年时间。<br><br> “我们继续看到对数字的请求不断增加，而且这种情况不会消失，”韦伯说。但没有什么是永恒的。 NANPA 一直在密切关注并为我们用完三位数区号或必须超越 10 位数区号的那一天做好准备。韦伯告诉我，根据 NANPA 的专有预测系统（该系统考虑了预测需求和分配率），“预计用尽日期”是 2051 年的某个时间。<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1880/06/a-telephonic-conversation/306078/">马克·吐温：一次电话交谈（1880 年 6 月起）</a><br><br> I shudder to think what will happen on that day. The dawn of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.zdnet.com/article/are-12-digit-phone-numbers-in-our-future/">longer phone numbers</a> is one possibility; surrendering to online services is another. The phone number feels a bit like a relic in the age of Zoom meetings, one-tap FaceTiming, WhatsApp, Signal, Viber, DMs, Discord—you name it. Phone numbers were originally conceived as a way to route connections via location, and technically speaking, the internet now does this just as well either via IP addresses or by using the Voice over Internet Protocol. The nerds <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://pocketnow.com/why-are-we-still-using-phone-numbers/">suggest</a> that we could ditch the numbering system and use a decentralized calling system that works a bit like web addresses do—you get a unique address and purchase a domain, so people can contact you without having to punch in a long string of numbers.<br><br> Still, it&#39;s worth considering what we lose if our area codes, prefixes, and line numbers are slowly washed away by the sands of time. If nothing more, it&#39;s worth appreciating these digits—an impersonal series of semi-random numbers that, once they&#39;re yours, take on a new life. When shared, a phone number is the most intimate of invitations, offering boundless possibilities of connection. It moors and orients us. That alone is a small miracle worth celebrating.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastructure/674735/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/phone-number-technology-infrastructure/674735/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Is Tennessee a Democracy?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> What happened when a Republican supermajority gained control—and wasn&#39;t satisfied <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/27TF7e4XH-or1LtfF2cywj_n4xQ=/0x0:2160x2700/648x810/media/img/2023/07/17/TheAtlantic_Tennessee_1_jul23_rt/original.jpg" alt="Tennesee State House in Red" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo-Illustration by Ricardo Tomás for The Atlantic. Source: Getty.</figcaption></figure> D <span class="smallcaps">rive along the outer rim</span> of the exurbs north of Nashville, past structures that might be barns or might be wedding venues, around developments called Vineyard Grove or New Hope Village, and eventually you will arrive at what is meant to be the new headquarters of the election commission of Sumner County, Tennessee. A featureless one-story brick warehouse with some makeshift offices attached, it has just enough space for the tiny handful of election-commission employees, the 275 voting machines that they recently purchased, and maybe some of the maintenance workers who used to share rooms with them, back when the agency was still in the basement of the county-administration building.<br><br> Dusty picnic tables crowd against the wall. An elementary school stands a few hundred yards away. Nothing about this building or its location screams “controversy.” But when Sumner County&#39;s local elections brought a faction that calls itself the Constitutional Republicans to power last year, that is what it nevertheless became.<br><br> To fully grasp this story, you need to understand that the standard forms of American political polarization don&#39;t exist in Sumner, a rural but rapidly suburbanizing county where Democrats are not part of the equation at all. None has won any county office for more than two decades. Instead, the main opponents of the Constitutional Republicans, who won 14 out of 17 seats on the county commission (following a general election in which only 15 percent of eligible voters cast ballots), are the ordinary Republicans—or, as their opponents would call them, RINOs (“Republicans in name only”). The Constitutional Republicans&#39; website explains that RINOs are different from themselves: “They raise taxes, they vote to silence the citizens, they won&#39;t protect private property rights. They often partner with Democrats to defeat true Constitutional Republicans like us.”<br><br> Upon taking over the county commission, the Constitutional Republicans <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/election-conspiracies-local-government-religion-republicans-tennessee-758307fb4856c91138c085ad70505841">issued a document</a> formally declaring that their activities will be “reflective of Judeo-Christian values inherent in the nation&#39;s founding.” They also shut down the HR department, tried to privatize a public historic building, and refused to pay for the election commission&#39;s move to the brick building, although it had been agreed by the previous administration. The old offices—three basement rooms that recently flooded—were too small to store the new voting machines, and also insecure. The entrance to the basement stood right beside a cashier&#39;s window where dozens of people were lined up to pay taxes on the day I visited. The county commissioners are unmoved by those arguments. “If we don&#39;t fund it, you don&#39;t get to do it,” Jeremy Mansfield, one of the Constitutional Republicans on the county commission, told the election commission at one public meeting about the move last fall. At a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYzcIZXfkmI">meeting in June</a> , another county commissioner, angered because the new voting machines had been delivered to the new building, said that although he would “hate to pull the ace card,” the commission could always “declare this property surplus, and sell it.” That would leave the election commission, and its machines, with nowhere to go.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/trump-induced-idiocy-tennessee/673726/">Peter Wehner: An acute attack of Trumpism in Tennessee</a><br><br> The building seems a small thing to get worked up about. But Facebook posts and videos of public meetings, all available online—the Constitutional Republicans are very transparent—make clear that this is not a trivial jurisdictional dispute and these are not petty people. They have ambitions and interests that extend well beyond their county. Their Facebook page reacted to the news of Donald Trump&#39;s latest indictment by declaring, “The Biden family is an organized crime family,” and “Our justice system is rigged against Trump.” Another post asked whether Tennessee “should secede from the Union.” More to the point, Mansfield, who didn&#39;t respond to my request for an interview (his view of the press is clear on his Facebook page, on which someone refers to the Associated Press as “American Pravda” and he responds “except that Pravda does more honest reporting”), wrote a long post back in February attacking early voting and voting machines: “The gold standard for election integrity would be paper ballots filled out by people and counted by people in local precincts on election day.”<br><br> The Constitutional Republicans are confident in these views for a reason. “Our beliefs are derived from the bible,” their website declares: “We pray at every meeting and we seek God in all we do! His wisdom guides our decisions.” The same source gives them confidence that their enemies are wrong. “Evil never sleeps,” Mansfield wrote on Facebook, after reflecting on the critics who he said were attacking him for fighting against new development in the county, “so we must heed Churchill&#39;s words, never give in, and never give up fighting for what is good and right.”<br><br> Few of these ambitious goals are within their reach. The Sumner County commissioners can&#39;t arrest President Joe Biden. They can&#39;t secede. But the county&#39;s election commission, whose members are appointed by the bipartisan state election commission, is right there. It&#39;s a local embodiment of the broader culture they dislike and of the government they distrust. If they can stick the agency back in the flood-prone basement, they will.<br><br> Tom Lee, the lawyer for the Sumner election commission—it is now suing the county—has an additional explanation as well. Lee points out that the Constitutional Republicans arrived in office wanting to enact deep, revolutionary change. That means that, whatever the previous regime decided, they are against it: “They are coming to power and saying, &#39;Everything that came before us doesn&#39;t count. We represent something new and different, and we don&#39;t have to have any allegiance to the past.&#39;” I told him that this sounded like the language used by the Bolsheviks, among other revolutionaries. He didn&#39;t laugh.<br><br> M <span class="smallcaps">ost of the time</span> , Tennessee politics doesn&#39;t make national news. That changed in April, when the leaders of the Republican supermajority in the Tennessee House of Representatives expelled two Democratic legislators, Justin Jones and Justin Pearson. The two men were accused of disrupting proceedings, because they repeated the demands of gun-control activists on the floor of the chamber, during a recess, using a megaphone.<br><br> The incident created a wave of outrage. The punishment seemed both extreme—since Reconstruction, only two people have been expelled from the Tennessee legislature, one for bribery and the other for alleged sexual misconduct—and racist, because it deliberately targeted two young Black men. A third protester, Representative Gloria Johnson, who is white, was allowed to keep her house seat. Belatedly, the Republicans who made this decision realized that it looked bad. At an acrimonious meeting held afterward (a tape of which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tnholler.com/2023/04/leaked-audio-tn-house-gop-caucus-infighting-over-tn-3-votes/">leaked to <i>The</i> <i>Tennessee Holler</i></a> , a local online publication), they expressed no regret at the expulsions, but they did berate one of the members for not voting to expel Johnson, on the grounds that leaving her out made them all seem like racists. The decision also made heroes of the protesters, now dubbed the Tennessee Three, a title previously bestowed on Johnny Cash&#39;s backup band. Jones and Pearson were reinstated by local officials, pending special elections in August, and became instant national stars.<br><br> But in truth, their story did not start on that day. Not so long ago, Tennessee was not merely a more bipartisan state but a <i>model</i> of bipartisanship, an example to others. Keel Hunt, a columnist for the <i>Tennessean</i> newspaper (and a Democrat who once worked for a Republican governor, Lamar Alexander), wrote a book about the 1980s and &#39;90s, an era when moderate Democrats and liberal Republicans ruled the state; when Tennessee sent Alexander, Howard Baker, Al Gore, and Jim Sasser to the US Senate; and when many of the decisions that paved the way for Tennessee&#39;s current investment boom were made. The book is called <i>Crossing the Aisle: How Bipartisanship Brought Tennessee to the Twenty-First Century and Could Save America</i> . So much has changed since then, Hunt told me, that the book “might now qualify as an obituary.”<br><br> Today, Tennessee is a model of one-party rule. It has a Republican governor and legislature. Republican appointees run the state supreme court. The state&#39;s nine-member US House delegation contains eight Republicans; Tennessee has sent two Republicans to the Senate. The governor is the only other official elected statewide. Unlike in other states, the attorney general and secretary of state in Tennessee are appointed, and they are both Republicans too.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/america-democracy-autocracy-laboratories/673751/">Brian Klaas: The red states experimenting with authoritarianism</a><br><br> Nor will the situation be easy to change, because gerrymandering is something of a blood sport in the state. The still-blue city of Nashville had a single Democrat representing it in Congress, but when the map was redrawn before the 2022 elections, GOP lawmakers split Nashville into three districts that stretch out into the countryside. Each elected a Republican. Instead of Jim Cooper, a Blue Dog moderate Democrat who held the seat for two decades, Nashville is now represented by, among others, Andy Ogles, who is best known for sending out a holiday card featuring himself, his children, and his wife all holding guns in front of a Christmas tree. State-level gerrymandering is just as vicious—Johnson reckons that one redistricting included a special effort to eliminate her from politics: “They split my precinct and drew a line basically a few blocks around my house to draw me out of the district,” she told me. (She moved, ran again, and won.)<br><br> Getting people to vote is not so easy, either, because Tennessee has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">some of the nation&#39;s most restrictive voting laws</a> . You can&#39;t register to vote any later than 30 days before the election. If you vote by absentee ballot, it has to arrive by mail on or before Election Day. There are no drop boxes. First-time voters have to vote in person, which is a special problem for college students studying out of state. In 2019, the legislature passed a law <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://stateline.org/2019/08/14/tennessee-made-it-harder-to-register-voters-activists-consider-whats-next/">subjecting voter-registration campaigners</a> to financial or criminal penalties if they submit too many erroneous forms—a provision that seemed designed to discourage get-out-the-vote campaigns, was blocked as unconstitutional, and later repealed. Perhaps none of these rules alone would seem outrageous. But the “cumulative effect,” argues Tricia Herzfeld, a Democrat who serves on Nashville&#39;s election commission, “is to make it hard to vote.” There is evidence for that theory: Tennessee has either one of the lowest or else the very lowest voter-turnout rates in the country, depending on how you count. And that, of course, is even before Sumner County moved to deprive its election commission of office space, conceivably making it difficult for anyone there to vote at all.<br><br> I <span class="smallcaps">came to Tennessee</span> partly because I wondered how similar it might feel to Poland and Hungary, where for the past decade I&#39;ve been warily observing the decline of democracy and the rise of the one-party state. The very large differences are immediately clear in Nashville, where music is the backdrop to everything, where everyone seems to be coming from a party or heading to one, where people on both sides of the political spectrum went out of their way to introduce me to other people. “This is a son-in-law kind of town,” someone told me. I wasn&#39;t quite sure what that meant (something to do with everyone looking after friends and relatives?), but it was amusing. For that and many other reasons, Nashville is not Budapest-on-the-Cumberland. The Bill of Rights still applies. Federal judges rule on Tennessee laws. The US Constitution is widely and even ostentatiously revered. There is no Central European gloom.<br><br> Nevertheless, the cascade of tiny legal and procedural changes designed to create an unlevel playing field, the ruling party&#39;s inexplicable sense of grievance, the displaced moderates with nowhere to go—this did seem familiar from other places. So was the sense that institutional politics has become performative, somehow separated from real life. The Tennessee Three staged their protest on the floor of the legislature, after all, because the conversation unfolding there had taken no notice of the much larger protests happening outside the chamber. A few days earlier, a horrific mass shooting at Covenant, a private Christian school in Nashville, had galvanized the public. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://news.vanderbilt.edu/2023/05/03/vanderbilt-poll-tennessee/">Opinion polls</a> showed that more than 70 percent of Tennesseans want red-flag laws that would allow officials to remove guns from people who might misuse them, while more than 80 percent support background checks and other gun-safety laws.<br><br> Those enormous majorities were not reflected in the legislative debate. In the days following the school shooting, it was just “business as usual,” Justin Kanew, the founder and editor of <i>The Tennessee Holler</i> , told me. Kanew, a transplant from California like a number of people in Nashville, is himself a former Democratic candidate for Congress in Tennessee. During his campaign, he saw a gap in the public conversation, and that experience led him to found the <i>Holler</i> . Or rather the Hollers: There are now several Twitter offshoots—the Chattanooga Holler, the Clarksville Holler, and so on—all focused on the hyperlocal issues that the statewide media were missing. Kanew&#39;s own talent is for a form of campaigning journalism: He produces short video clips, often of state legislators, and then circulates them on social media. Sometimes they go viral. That&#39;s what he was doing on the day the Tennessee Three made their protest. “There were thousands of people showing up at the capitol,” he told me, “asking for something to happen. And if nothing had happened, that would have been pretty deflating.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/04/tennessee-expulsions-republican-gop/673709/">Read: The Tennessee expulsions are just the beginning</a><br><br> This was not the first time that the Republican leadership sought to shut down debate. The house&#39;s “two Justins,” as they are now known, brought their megaphone precisely because the Republican leadership commonly turns off Democrats&#39; microphones when they are speaking. Representative Bo Mitchell was once cut off when he told the house, “Please don&#39;t say you are pro-life and put more weapons on the street”—a statement ruled to be insulting. Jones told me that he was ruled out of order during a committee meeting because he&#39;d said the leadership was “putting a Band-Aid on the issue” of school shootings; a few days later he was also told he had to remove a <span class="smallcaps">ban assault weapons</span> pin from his jacket. Republicans insist, as Tennessee House Majority Leader William Lamberth <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/NC5PhilWilliams/status/1661524250019201024?s=20">told a local television station</a> , that speakers are meant to stick to the topic: “It&#39;s not open-mic night.”<br><br> “They are coming to power and saying, &#39;Everything that came before us doesn&#39;t count. We represent something new and different, and we don&#39;t have to have any allegiance to the past.&#39;”<br><br> Under relatively recent rules, individual members&#39; question time has been cut from 15 minutes to five. Occasionally, people who want to raise objections are not called on at all. During a debate on a bill regulating abortion, Gloria Johnson told me, “I stood on the house floor for 45 minutes, the entire argument of the bill, and they refused to call on me.” These tactics are new. Johnson, who has served in the legislature on and off for more than a decade, told me that although the house also had a Republican supermajority when she joined in 2012, the speaker at that time didn&#39;t exclude Democrats from debate. “I don&#39;t recall her refusing to call on me,” she said. Jones, who was a community organizer in Nashville for a decade before being elected, agreed that previous speakers were more open to conversation. “This was the most extreme session I have ever seen,” he said. “Republicans now treat the legislature as a private palace, a fraternity house or a country club.”<br><br> Nor is radicalization visible only in the legislature. Just as Hungary&#39;s Viktor Orbán fights with opposition-controlled Budapest (and Turkey&#39;s Recep Tayyip Erdoğan fights with Istanbul, and Poland&#39;s Jarosław Kaczyński fights with Warsaw), so do Tennessee Republicans fight with opposition-controlled Nashville. Over breakfast at the Elliston Place Soda Shop—he likes showing off the city sites—Nashville Mayor John Cooper, a Democrat (and brother of Jim Cooper, the former member of Congress), ticked off the various disputes between the city and the state with a certain level of weariness: about <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/04/03/faa-intervenes-in-dispute-over-nashville-airport-leadership/70076289007/">control over the airport</a> , about the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.adamsandreese.com/last-call/fate-of-metro-nashville-beer-board-remains-uncertain-at-tennessee-general-assembly">beer board</a> , about the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/03/09/bills-to-take-over-nashville-airport-sports-authority-boards-advance/69985037007/">sports authority</a> , about the size of the city council (Republicans tried to cut it from 40 members to 20), and about the 2024 Republican National Convention—which, partly thanks to all of the other quarrels, will not take place in Nashville.<br><br> Some of the disputes are just about who controls the money, but he thinks real cultural friction underlies those too. Whereas Nashville used to be what the mayor calls a “big county-seat kind of town,” famous for its music clubs, now it&#39;s also a focus of international investment, health-care investment, and tech investment. Oracle is building a $1 billion–plus campus in the city; Amazon has a major presence here too. On the morning we met, Mayor Cooper was jet-lagged, having just returned from Kurdistan. He went there because Nashville, aside from being the city that launched Taylor Swift, is also home to one of the largest Kurdish communities in America. After breakfast, he drove me to the East Bank, the site of the city&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nashville.gov/departments/planning/long-range-planning/local-planning-studies/east-bank-planning-study">next major development project</a> , one that will include a new stadium, new housing, and some infrastructure renovations; along the way, we passed a remarkable collection of building sites, replete with giant cranes. Still, in the conservative mediaverse, Nashville&#39;s city leaders are just another set of enemies. Fox News once devoted a whole segment to Cooper—in which <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/virus-outbreak-marsha-blackburn-nashville-tucker-carlson-tennessee-d8370b1bab309d954a8b6b7fb5547d39">Tucker Carlson accused him, falsely</a> , of concealing information about COVID.<br><br> Kanew (and he isn&#39;t alone) thinks the state serves as a kind of “guinea pig,” a test market in this same mediaverse, a place where new culture-war themes can be experimentally stoked. A war on judges as well as on remote voting began in 2021, when the chair of a key house subcommittee <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2021/03/02/support-grows-nashville-judge-ellen-hobbs-lyle-targeted-lawmaker/6878391002/">sought to remove a judge</a> who had ruled in favor of expanding the right to vote by mail during the pandemic. Last September, the governor and other Republicans <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/">lashed out at Vanderbilt University Medical Center</a> , allegedly for suppressing employees who criticized the university&#39;s gender clinic, charges the university denied. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://eu.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2022/09/21/vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-faces-gop-criticism-investigation-republican/69508530007/"> </a>More recently, the state attorney general has investigated the clinic, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tennesseelookout.com/2023/06/22/ag-made-sweeping-demands-for-vanderbilt-transgender-clinic-records-as-part-of-fraud-inquiry/?eType=EmailBlastContent&amp;eId=0bdfc350-1039-4564-94e1-7a42e32a226c">demanding private medical records</a> .<br><br> Sometimes these efforts are clawed back. A determined group of local lawyers and lobbyists helped get some exceptions for the life of the mother enshrined into the state&#39;s abortion ban. A Trump-appointed federal judge <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/13/opinion/tennessee-trump-maga-justin-jones-pearson.html">recently overturned</a> another culture-war gesture, a Tennessee law banning public drag performances, on the grounds that it chilled free speech. But whether individual pieces of hard-line legislation stick might not matter, because part of the point of passing them is just to allow local politicians to align themselves with the general views of that same conservative mediaverse. One example: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://trackbill.com/bill/tennessee-senate-joint-resolution-174-memorials-recognition-danube-institute/2353243/">a recent resolution</a> passed by the legislature to “recognize and commend” Orbán&#39;s think tank, the Danube Institute, which promotes illiberal and antidemocratic ideas. Jones, objecting to that resolution, asked Tim Hicks, the Republican who proposed it, if he knew who Orbán was. <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/thetnholler/status/1648811745064935425?s=46&amp;t=QfucpGynsbxt5jS-672ayA">He did not</a> . One disgruntled Republican described this whole process to me as “governing by anecdote.” You could also describe it as “governing by Fox News.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2022/01/children-sex-trafficking-conspiracy-epidemic/620845/">From the January/February 2022 issue: The great (fake) child-sex-trafficking epidemic</a><br><br> But every so often, a glimpse of something uglier appears, a hint that some people want more than culture wars designed for TikTok, Twitter, and the evening news. Walking to her home in Nashville, an acquaintance saw a car with a <span class="smallcaps">shoot your local pedophile</span><i> </i>bumper sticker, showing an outline of a man holding a gun to another man&#39;s head. T-shirts with this image, phrasing, and implied approval of violence are for sale online. “This isn&#39;t new to you, but it&#39;s new to us,” she told me, which isn&#39;t quite true. Poland, where I live part of the time, has had <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-46878325">one political murder</a> in recent years, but it was a knife murder. In Tennessee, people have guns. Jim Cooper, the former member of Congress, told me that getting anyone to run for office as a Democrat in some rural parts of the state is difficult partly because <i>Democrat</i> and <i>pedophile</i> are so often conflated by Republican activists, and potential candidates are spooked. About half of the state-legislature seats were uncontested in 2022.<br><br> Not that the problem of finding Democrats to run for office is new. Cooper also told me that one of his staff used to comb through local newspapers and look for people who had written angry letters to the editor. Then she would call them up and ask them to stand for election. Some said yes. Though most of them lost, he considered that a kind of victory. Jones thinks that after the expulsion crisis, “young people are fired up, bringing urgency to our politics,” and that more candidates will come forward. But there will be a steep road to climb if people fear that what is at stake in their local election is not tax rates and building permits but the safety and even the lives of their children—and if they fight back with real weapons.<br><br> If that possibility sounds ludicrous, or incredible, it shouldn&#39;t. Kanew, the <i>Tennessee Holler</i> editor, woke up one night last April to the sound of gunfire. Someone had shot up the front of his house. No one has yet been arrested.<br><br> “Y <span class="smallcaps">ou know the old saying:</span> All politics is national.” That&#39;s what the mayor of Nashville told me over his ham and eggs. “All politics is national,” several other people said to me too. It&#39;s a joke—“All politics is local” is the old political chestnut—but also not a joke. In the past couple of years, prominent and less-prominent conservatives have been flocking from all over the country to Tennessee and, more precisely, to Williamson County, adjacent to Nashville and, partly thanks to that proximity, now one of the wealthiest counties in the country. The town of Franklin, Williamson&#39;s county seat, has a large and well-lit (I visited at night) monument to the soldiers of the Confederacy. It is also home to equally monumental culture-war clashes and school-board battles that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/23/opinion/school-boards-books-tennessee.html">can rival those anywhere else in the country</a> . The <i>New York Times</i> columnist David French, who lives there, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/06/opinion/maga-america-trump.html">reckons</a> that “only 15 percent of my neighbors are Democrats.” The Daily Wire, a conservative media company that specializes in culture-war clashes and school-board battles, is now based in Nashville, as are a handful of its stars.<br><br> Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should.<br><br> “All politics is national” is also the explanation that a lot of people gave me when I asked how Tennessee went from having a culture of bipartisanship to de facto one-party rule in a mere two decades. Almost everybody wanted to explain that Tennessee politics used to reflect the state&#39;s particular geography (mountains in the east, Mississippi River Delta in the west, rivers and forest in the middle) and complicated history. Some Tennesseans had declared for the Confederacy; others fought against it. The Ku Klux Klan was founded in Pulaski, Tennessee; Nashville was the site of a series of sit-ins that were important to the civil-rights movement. The disgruntled Republicans in particular <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnas.org/publications/blog/two-cheers-for-tennessee">mourn the death</a> of what used to be called “Tennessee enlightened mountain Republicanism,” the liberal, business-oriented party that once challenged the pre-civil-rights “Old South” Democratic one-party state, which relied on Jim Crow and voter suppression. For a long time, both parties celebrated the demise of that system, and no one wanted it back. Or so it seemed.<br><br> By some accounts, the shift began in the 1990s, during the Clinton administration, when talk radio and a confrontational new style of national media began to weaken the local newspapers that people used to read, and the local culture too. Others think the turning point came in the 2000s, when Barack Obama&#39;s presidency produced a racist backlash. In 2012, one poll showed that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/sorry-obama-birtherism-is-alive-and-well-2012-3?IR=T">nearly half of Tennessee Republicans</a> believed in the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/05/birtherism-and-trump/610978/">birtherism conspiracy theory</a> .<br><br> Still others think the harder shift inside the Republican Party began more recently, <i>after</i> it gained full control. John Geer, a Vanderbilt political scientist, told me that whenever a supermajority controls a legislature for a long period of time, “those in the minority have no political ability to effect change, and so they stop acting like politicians and instead become activists,” a thesis that explains the actions of the Tennessee Three, as well as the feeling that politics has become a form of performance art, only distantly related to real life.<br><br> But the supermajority is also affected, and its members become activists of a different kind. To stay in office in a state where few people vote and districts are gerrymandered, Tennessee legislators need to appeal to only a tiny number of very dedicated, very partisan people. The competition for those votes can quite quickly turn into a competition for who can sound most radical. Even the minority leader of the Tennessee State Senate, Raumesh Akbari, a Democrat, told me that it&#39;s harder to do deals with people from heavily gerrymandered districts: “You don&#39;t have anybody to check you and your district is extremely partisan.” Her own district skews heavily Democratic and heavily Black. “If I wasn&#39;t someone who was willing to compromise, I wouldn&#39;t have to,” Akbari said.<br><br> There is another element: Call it the lesson of Sumner County, the place where Republicans won everything, control everything, and yet <i>still</i> feel aggrieved and victimized. As in Hungary or Poland or as in <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/02/venezuelas-suffering-shows-where-illiberalism-leads/606988/">Venezuela</a> , the experience of radicalism can make people more radical. Total control of a political system can make the victors not more magnanimous, but more frustrated, not least because they learn that total control still doesn&#39;t deliver what they think it should. No county commission or state legislature can possibly meet the demands of a quasi-religious movement that believes it has God on its side and that its opponents herald the apocalypse. But that doesn&#39;t mean they give up. It just means they keep trying, using any tool available. Eventually they arrive at the point described by Tom Lee, the lawyer for the Sumner County Election Commission: “It&#39;s not enough to get your majority and get your way—they have to make the minority lose their voice.”<br><br> On the tape leaked to <i>The</i> <i>Tennessee Holler</i> after the expulsion of Pearson and Jones, this dynamic is powerfully revealed. Grim Republican legislators talked about what they think is really at stake, and it isn&#39;t megaphones. “If you don&#39;t believe we are at war for our republic,” one of them says to the group, “with all love and respect to you, you need a different job.” They don&#39;t believe that this is a normal political competition, either, or that their opponents are a normal, legitimate, small- <i>d</i> democratic opposition. Democrats, says another, “are not our friends.” They “destroy our republic and the foundation of who we are.” At one point, an apocalyptic tone creeps into the conversation: “The left wants Tennessee so bad because if they get us, the Southeast falls and it&#39;s &#39;game over&#39; for the republic.” So urgent and so dramatic is this challenge that some of them have come to believe that rules might have to be broken: “You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong,” one of them says.<br><br> <i>You gotta do what&#39;s right, even if you think it might be wrong. Fight for the republic</i> , <i>because otherwise it will be “game over</i> ”: The language itself wouldn&#39;t be unusual, if this were a radical minority fighting for its very existence. But this is the Republican Party, the party that controls pretty much everything in Tennessee. They are going to win the next election, and probably the one after that. Yet they sound as if winning isn&#39;t enough: They also want their opponents to fall silent, and they are doing what they can to make that happen.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 18 Jul 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/tennessee-republican-partisanship-one-party-state/674732/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Remote-Work Debate Stays So Heated]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The conversation often foregrounds large-scale issues such as productivity and company culture, but the question of where an employee works is intensely personal. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C9uTFuz-5brHPsAys00WYgH6Pc8=/0x266:5121x3147/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_862664210/original.jpg" alt="People pass a building at night" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Peter Cade / Getty</figcaption></figure> <small><i>This is an edition of</i> The Atlantic <i>Daily, a newsletter that guides you through the biggest stories of the day, helps you discover new ideas, and recommends the best in culture.</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>Sign up for it here.</i></a></small><br><br> The physical space in which a person works, or hopes to work, intersects with their most personal choices. Today we&#39;re checking in on the remote-work debate and why it remains so heated.<br><br> First, here are four new stories from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">The businessmen broke Hollywood.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">Goodbye to the prophets of doom.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/">I have cancer. I can&#39;t put my kids first anymore.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/">Joe Lieberman weighs the Trump risk.</a></li> <strong>Better Together?</strong><br><br> In the summer of 2021, I started going back to the office. It was not the allure of watercooler chatter or the promise of juiced-up productivity that pulled me in. At the time, I just really wanted to sit in the AC. It was June; it was hot. Access to a desk in a freezing-cold Midtown tower—a far cry from my living room, which tended to get steamy on 90-degree Brooklyn days—seemed like a major perk. I was living with roommates, was vaccinated, and had no child-care duties. Each morning, I strapped on my mask and packed my backpack with canisters of coffee and sandwiches to sustain me through the day. I often felt better when I got home: When you&#39;re going into an office, I found, it&#39;s harder to have a day where nothing happens.<br><br> My desire to return to a routine that involved leaving my home was inspired, in part, by my now-colleague Ellen Cushing&#39;s 2021 <i>Atlantic</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/03/what-pandemic-doing-our-brains/618221/">article</a> about what the monotony of the pandemic was doing to our brain. “Sometimes I imagine myself as a Sim, a diamond-shaped cursor hovering above my head as I go about my day. Tasks appear, and I do them. Mealtimes come, and I eat. Needs arise, and I meet them,” she writes in one memorable passage. In another, she quotes an expert saying that “environmental enrichment”—seeing new people, observing new things on a commute—is good for our brain&#39;s plasticity. After reading the article in March 2021, I became fixated on the idea that observing random humans on my commute would keep my mind sharp.<br><br> Then the fall came around, and so did more of my colleagues. It was great to see them. It was also great, sometimes, to return to the relative solitude of my home and take walks in Prospect Park at midday. I was lucky to have that flexibility. Now that I work for <i>The Atlantic</i> , I go into the office almost every day. I have enjoyed meeting new people and, again, sitting in the industrial-grade AC.<br><br> I&#39;ve given you this narration of my personal experience because, for all the talk of productivity and metrics and company culture, the topic of returning to the office is intensely personal. My needs and desires, for a variety of reasons relating to my age, finances, circumstances, health situation, and lifestyle, might be very different from those of workers who fall elsewhere on any of those axes. Some working parents have said they might value flexibility at school-pickup time. Some workers of color have raised the benefit of being free from <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://hbr.org/2022/05/research-the-real-time-impact-of-microaggressions">in-office microaggressions</a> . Recent college graduates may want to go into the office to make friends. And of course, not all workers are able to work remotely. The physical space in which one works, or hopes to work, intersects with one&#39;s most personal choices. It collides with and reveals what people value most.<br><br> Nick Bloom, a Stanford economics professor who studies remote work, told me that “research and evidence are slowly catching up” to the work-from-home debate. In five years, he predicted, the topic will be less controversial. Bloom and two colleagues, Jose Maria Barrero and Steven J. Davis, published a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kqbngD8pemqxAkZmWCOQ32Yk6PXK9eVA/view">working paper</a> earlier this month that collects some of the existing work-from-home research, pulling both from their own work and from other papers. One interesting finding is that although fully remote work has been correlated with a drop in productivity, hybrid work (which occurs widely in white-collar fields such as tech and business services) was not linked to any productivity loss—and could actually <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://siepr.stanford.edu/publications/working-paper/evolution-working-home">help with recruitment and retention</a> .<br><br> Workers gained freedom over their working conditions in the past few years. Now <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/20/business/return-to-office-remote-work.html">many bosses</a> are trying to wrest that power back. And workers and managers don&#39;t always see eye to eye about the stakes of returning to work. Bloom and his colleagues asked managers and employees about how working from home affected productivity. Workers, on the whole, said they were 7.4 percent more productive on average while working from home; bosses said that they thought their employees were 3.5 percent less productive. Managers tend to most appreciate what they can see in front of them, Bloom told me over email: “It&#39;s like those restaurants where the kitchen is open and on display—it feels more like you are having a fantastic culinary experience, but it&#39;s really just a mirage.”<br><br> Companies&#39; <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/31/business/work-home-return-office-amazon.html">rationales</a> for calling people back to work can seem mushy, beyond that it simply seems like being together would be better (or, in some cases, that employers want to fulfill expensive real-estate obligations). One argument for working in person is the idea that younger workers can learn from, and be mentored by, more experienced colleagues in the workplace. Bloom told me that senior managers over the age of 50 provide about 50 percent of the mentoring minutes when working from home as they do while in the office. “A lot of mentoring is casual, relaxed conversations and, yes, it&#39;s spontaneous—taking somebody aside and giving some quick advice,” he said. A Pew Research Center survey from March found that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/03/30/about-a-third-of-us-workers-who-can-work-from-home-do-so-all-the-time/">36 percent of teleworkers</a> said remote work hurt their opportunities to be mentored. Positive remote mentoring can happen (I found a formal mentorship program conducted mostly over Zoom very useful). Bloom said that although in theory—and with the right software—these types of relationships can blossom, “practically this does not happen as much online.”<br><br> Bloom&#39;s point (and my reaction to it) reinforces how personal experience can color perspectives on this issue: In my case, I both relish time away from home and believe in the potential of remote mentor relationships. But how those dimensions of work fit into our lives can vary widely. Change any inputs—personal commute time, age, nature of work, child-care responsibilities, goals—and the resulting approach may be unrecognizable.<br><br> <b>Related</b> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/us-remote-work-impact-fertility-rate-babies/673301/">The surprising effects of remote work</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/good-management-mentorship-remote-world/621219/">How to mentor young workers in a remote world</a></li> <strong>Today&#39;s News</strong><br><br><li> Russia is halting the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/17/world/europe/ukraine-russia-grain-deal.html">Black Sea Grain Initiative</a> , which ensured that Ukraine could export its grain by sea despite a wartime blockade and helped stabilize global food prices.</li><li> Senator Joe Manchin&#39;s decision to headline an event with the No Labels organization is <a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-senator-manchin-speech-stokes-speculation-white-house-run-2023-07-17/">fueling speculation</a> over a potential third-party presidential run.</li><li> Firefighters are <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/16/us/california-wildfires-extreme-heat/index.html">battling several wildfires</a> in Southern California that ignited this weekend amid excessive heat warnings.</li> <b>Evening Read</b><br><br> Do Yourself a Favor and Go Find a &#39;Third Place&#39;<br><br> <em>By Allie Conti</em><br><br><p> On a Sunday last year, I was walking through a suburban neighborhood in Pennsylvania, heading home from an early-afternoon meditation class. One of the nondescript stucco houses had a curious sticker on its mailbox reading mac&#39;s club. I checked Google Maps to see if I was standing next to a cleverly disguised business—what might pretentiously be referred to in a city as a speakeasy—but nothing popped up, so I peeked inside the house. That&#39;s where I spotted a pool table and a middle-aged guy sitting at the end of a long, mahogany bar, drinking a Bloody Mary by himself. Apparently I&#39;d stumbled upon a social club meant for residents of the neighborhood. Though at first the bartender was incredulous that I&#39;d just walked in, he soon rewarded my sense of adventure with a Guinness on the house. The Eagles weren&#39;t playing in the NFL that day, and he was grateful for the additional company. We talked about the upcoming deer season, and upon learning that I was a new hunter, the two guys showed me a rifle that was kept in another room. ……</p><p> Besides giving me the feeling that I&#39;d flexed a muscle that had atrophied, the interaction was special to me because I&#39;d found a classic “third place” in the suburbs, where I least expected it. The term, which was coined by the sociologist Ray Oldenburg in the 1980s, essentially refers to a physical location other than work or home where there&#39;s little to no financial barrier to entry and where conversation is the primary activity.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/04/third-places-meet-new-people-pandemic/629468/">Read the full article.</a><br><br> <b>More From <em>The Atlantic</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/">Elizabeth Bruenig: Alabama wants to kill Jimi Barber.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/">The most shocking aspect of RFK Jr.&#39;s anti-Semitism</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/">Delivery apps just did the impossible.</a></li> <b>Culture Break</b><br><br><b>读。</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/mozart-in-motion-his-work-and-his-world-in-pieces-patrick-mackie/9780374606206?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Mozart in Motion</i></a> , by the British poet Patrick Mackie, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/mozart-in-motion-book-review-music/674726/">explores the secret to Mozart&#39;s lasting appeal</a> .<br><br> <b>Watch.</b> Beneath the hijinks and lewdness, the show <i>Dave</i> (streaming on Hulu) constructs <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/">an unlikely model</a> for male friendship.<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">Play our daily crossword.</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>I like to bake, and find doing so relaxing. But in the summer, when my apartment is hot, I turn to treats that don&#39;t require baking. (In case it hasn&#39;t become clear: I do not enjoy the sensation of being overheated.) One very easy and fun one I have returned to is these <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018460-chocolate-peanut-butter-cups">chocolate-peanut-butter cups</a> , courtesy of Samantha Seneviratne. I don&#39;t have a double boiler or a microwave, so I boil water in a saucepan and melt chocolate chips in a metal bowl on top of it. And I like cashew butter, so I use that instead of peanut butter. The effort-to-reward ratio is high: These take just a few minutes of active work and render delightful little treats.<br><br> — Lora<br><br> <i>Katherine Hu contributed to this newsletter.</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Businessmen Broke Hollywood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>现在他们不想支付员工工资。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0uua5U8CtPMn05n96loBLb7ojPs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/hollywood_strike/original.jpg" alt="好莱坞演员罢工的照片。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大卫·布托 / Redux</figcaption></figure>好莱坞机器——从剧本写作、拍摄和制作，到深夜脱口秀公关——已经正式停止运转。<br><br>周四， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">演员们举行罢工。</a>在无所畏惧的情景喜剧保姆弗兰·德雷舍 (Fran Drescher) 的领导下，SAG-AFTRA 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">16 万名成员</a>在与制片厂的谈判破裂后停止了工作。他们加入了美国作家协会的行列，该协会的成员（包括我本人）自五月以来一直在罢工。<br><br>自 1960 年以来，我们两个工会就没有一起罢工过。拍摄地点的编剧纠察队已经关闭了估计 80% 的制作。现在，美国演员工会的罢工规则规定，演员不仅不能为作品拍摄或做配音工作，而且还不能为作品拍摄或配音。他们也不能参加红地毯或宣传任何电影协会的项目——这已经是一个挑战，因为编剧罢工已经关闭了作为新闻界主要内容的夜间脱口秀节目。<br><br>就像编剧一样，演员们也在寻求增加剩余报酬——类似于版税支票的补偿——曾经可靠的收入在转向流媒体的过程中几乎消失了。演员们也在利用他们的声音和图像寻求针对人工智能的保护。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">霍奇特尔·冈萨雷斯：“一切都从我们开始”</a><br><br>迪士尼首席执行​​官鲍勃·艾格 (Bob Iger) 称这些期望“不现实”。他指责罢工者“增加了该行业已经面临的一系列挑战，坦率地说，这些挑战非常具有破坏性和危险性。”<br><br>就在几天前，一位工作室高管告诉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/writers-strike-hollywood-studios-deal-fight-wga-actors-1235434335/"><i>Deadline</i></a> ，他们的策略是“让事情拖延下去，直到工会成员开始失去他们的公寓和房子”。<br><br>驱逐是一种相当残酷的劳资谈判策略。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官们<i>正在</i>遭受苦难。主要不是来自劳资纠纷、行业混乱或公共关系问题，而是来自明显的无知，这似乎是所有行业高管的普遍现象。在向华尔街交付的压力下，太多的首席执行官失去了自己电影的情节。他们经营公司并不是为了盈利地提供优质产品，例如一本书或一杯咖啡，或者在这种情况下，是一部电影或电视节目。他们经营公司是为了创造丰厚的利润。他们的产品质量已经不再重要。<br><br>如果你对此表示怀疑，请考虑一下上周宣布艾美奖提名时，最大的份额流向了 HBO Max，这个享有盛誉的平台已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.insiderintelligence.com/content/charting-new-course-adapting-advertising-landscape-after-hbo-max-discovery-merger">不再以该名称存在</a>，因为华纳兄弟探索频道 (Warner Bros. Discovery) 接管了这个传统品牌的流媒体部门，并且把它折叠成一个杂乱的应用程序，里面挤满了低预算的真人秀节目。我们处于颠倒的状态。<br><br>作家和演员都陷入了流媒体的转向，其疯狂的逻辑<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/writers-guild-contract-negotiation-mini-room-1235568173/">颠覆了长期的工作实践</a>，慢慢开始用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/28/18637135/hollywood-ai-film-decision-script-analysis-data-machine-learning">人工智能</a>取代人类本能，并消除了工人的收入来源。<br><br>例如，演员马克·普罗克什 (Mark Proksch) 在<i>《办公室》</i>中客串一季的剩余收入中赚了更多钱，<i> </i>在旧体制下，比他在新体制下主演<i>《我们在阴影中做什么》</i>五季还要多<i>。</i><br><br>现在，正当好莱坞工作人员认为我们需要调整薪酬模式以适应流媒体时代时，制片厂却告诉我们，我们无法获得公平的报酬，因为流媒体模式已被打破。正是那些打破了这一规则的工作室高管——其中许多是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/ceo-pay-wga-writers-strike-1235351572/">千万富翁</a>——告诉了我们这一点。<br><br>这是最高管理层无知的另一个方面：疯狂的高管薪酬让领导者完全脱离了他们雇用的员工的生活。华纳兄弟和探索频道的首席执行官大卫·扎斯拉夫 (David Zaslav) 2021 年收入为 2.47 亿美元，这一事实让人很难接受他拒绝在每年导致中产阶级演员损失数千美元的问题上做出让步的事实。<br><br>你可以随心所欲地争论是否有人应该赚这么多钱，但这些领导者做出了一些灾难性的商业决策。<br><br>在大流行期间每个人都被困在家里的短暂时刻，转向流媒体是非常有利可图的。人们不能在音乐会、外出就餐或旅行上花钱，因此他们在流媒体服务上花费异常金额感到放心。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官看到了 Netflix 的成功，竞相复制一种模式，但不知道这种模式是否可持续，这种模式依赖于工会人才不断生产新的（且昂贵的）娱乐内容。他们对企业的看法是错误的，但更错误的是他们认为劳工会遵守规定。这个支点不是演员和编剧做出的，而是演员和编剧做出的。他们为什么要付出代价？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">阅读：为什么你应该关注好莱坞编剧的罢工</a><br><br>如果转向流媒体是一个错误，导致这些企业真的陷入困境——考虑到这些高管薪酬方案的规模，这种情况很难成立——我们也将不得不受苦。但如果我们在困难时期受苦，我们也应该在富裕时期分享利润。这就是谈判的目的。高管们能够纠正这艘船的唯一方法就是重新制作不容错过的节目，如果没有我们，他们将无法做到这一点。<br><br>由于缺乏优秀的剧本作家，好莱坞的高管们只能借鉴玛丽·安托瓦内特的台词。但革命者已经在外面拆除了宫殿。在伦敦，<i>奥本海默</i>的演员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oppenheimer-stars-walk-out-london-premiere-actors-strike-emily-blunt-matt-damon-florence-pugh-cillian-murphy/">走出了</a>电影的首映式。<i>芭比娃娃</i>的新闻发布会已停止；就连明星们粉红色的社交媒体账户也被黑了。艾美奖颁奖典礼可能会被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/21/business/media/emmy-awards-writers-strike.html">推迟</a>。动漫展将没有演员或作家。我非常希望电影公司能够早日认识到，即使这会暂时伤害股东，但从长远来看，好的娱乐永远是好生意。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 19:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Voicebot Just Left Me Speechless]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>生成式人工智能解决了困扰我的语音助手多年的问题。<br>说出我的名字 Saahil Desai 并不难。 Saahil：与<em>锯木厂</em>押韵，或者至少可以让你达到 90%。 Desai：就像<em>决定</em>把最后一点砍掉。确实如此。<br><br>然而，我的名字常常会被淹没在一大堆失态和错误中。最常见的一个，Sa <em>-heel</em> ，至少是一个诚实的尝试——不像它的突变双胞胎，一个单音节的混乱，听起来像<em>海豹。</em>其他人则违背了所有可能的逻辑。有一次，一位大学同学读到我的名字，停顿了一下，然后自信地说：“嗨，西雅图。”<br><br>但最让我烦恼的错误发音却不是任何人都能说出来的。它们来自机器人。一整天，Siri 都会通过塞在我耳朵里的 AirPods 读出我的短信，并将我的名字混入<em>Sahul</em>中。它比我用来转录采访的人工智能服务要好，后者通过一串似乎从失败的英国男孩乐队中剥离出来的名字（奈杰尔、萨尔、迈克尔、丹尼尔、斯科特·希尔）来识别我。硅谷渴望其产品能够改变世界，但显然这也意味着名称的改变<em>。</em><br><br>或者至少我是这么认为的。听听这个： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567406875&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/eleven-labs" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="十一个实验室">Eleven Labs</a>这是来自 ElevenLabs 的一个名为 Adam 的人工智能声音，ElevenLabs 是一家专门从事语音克隆的初创公司。 （这有点像音频中的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/09/ai-art-generators-future/671568/">DALL-E</a> 。）这个机器人不仅能很好地说出我的名字，而且还能很好地说出我的名字。它比我能更好地说出我的名字。毕竟，萨希尔来自梵语，而我不会说这种语言。最终的结果是一种熟悉的多巴胺的冲击，一种令人惊奇的感觉，就像在技术上找到一个刻有你名字的纪念品钥匙链一样。<br><br>除了可以写俳句的聊天机器人和可以按照毕加索风格绘制披萨的艺术机器人之外，生成式人工智能革命还催生了最终可以确定我的名字的语音机器人。正如 ChatGPT 从互联网帖子中学习到的那样，ElevenLabs 在大量音频片段上训练其声音，以了解如何像人们一样说话——至少<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">500,000 小时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">，而</a>早期语音模型需要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://research.facebook.com/file/649409006862002/paper_fixed.pdf">数十或数百</a>小时的音频。 “我们在过去两年里一直在开发一种新的语音基础模型，”ElevenLabs 首席执行官 Mati Staniszewski 在一封电子邮件中写道。 “这意味着我们的模型是上下文感知且与语言无关的，因此能够更好地捕捉名称等细微差别，并提供反映文本输入的语调和情感。”较新的语音机器人的数据可能包括任意数量的专门用于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.howtopronounce.com/">发音的</a>网站，如果有人在有声读物、播客或 YouTube 视频中正确说出了你的名字，较新的人工智能模型可能会记录下来。<br><br>亚马逊、谷歌、Meta 和微软等公司也在开发更先进的语音机器人——尽管它们仍然是鱼龙混杂。我在他们每个人的人工智能语音程序上测试了同一句话——“来吧，说 Saahil Desai 并不难”。他们都能应付德赛，但迎接我的却不是萨希尔完美发音的合唱。亚马逊的 Polly 软件可能比 Siri 更糟糕，它认为我的名字类似于 Saaaaal： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567407838&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/amazon-polly" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="亚马逊波莉">Amazon Polly</a>谷歌云和 Microsoft Azure 都无伤大雅，但并不完美，稍微将 Saahil 扭曲成一种明显陌生的东西。没有什么可以打败 ElevenLabs，但 Voicebox（Meta 尚未发布的工具）非常接近：该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.facebook.com/blog/voicebox-generative-ai-model-speech/">最近将其吹捧</a>为“语音生成人工智能的突破”： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567408888&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/meta-voicebox" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="元语音盒">Meta Voicebox</a>计算机现在可以说出比我自己的名字更多的名字。 “前几天，当我和我的学生在 CNN 的安德森·库珀 (Anderson Cooper) 的 ElevenLabs 上录制了一段录音时，我注意到了同样的事情，说‘哈尼·法里德教授是一个彻头彻尾的废物’（这是一个很长的故事），”汉尼·法里德 (Hany Farid) 说道。加州大学伯克利分校计算机科学家在一封电子邮件中写道。 “我很惊讶它能很好地发音我的名字。我还注意到它可以正确发音我的非美国学生的名字。”我测试过的其他棘手的名字也表现良好：ElevenLabs 确定了 Lupita Nyong&#39;o 和 Timothée Chalamet，尽管它把可怜的 Pete Buttigieg 的姓氏变成了非常不幸的 Buttygig。<br><br>人工智能声音现在可以说出不寻常的名字，这可不是一件小事。他们面临着同样的发音困难，这让许多人感到困惑。像 Giannis Antetokounmpo 这样的名字不遵守英语规则，而即使是一个更简单的名字也可以有多种发音（And <em>rea</em>或<em>And</em> rea？）或拼写（Michaela？ Mikayla？ Mikayla？ Michela？）。 Farid 表示，如果 AI 声音的颜色和纹理听起来比人类的 HAL 9000 更高，那么这个名字可能仍然听起来平淡无奇。<br><br>前几代语音助手——Siri、Alexa、Google Assistant、汽车的 GPS——只是没有足够的信息来完成所有这些步骤。 （在某些情况下，你可以自己提供这些信息：Apple 的一位发言人告诉我，你可以在通讯录应用程序中手动输入姓名的拼音，以调整 Siri 的读取方式。）多年来，这项技术“确实处于停滞状态” ，”法里德写道。 “它真的很难穿过那个恐怖谷，它有点像人类，但也有点奇怪。然后它就直接冲破了门。”受人脑启发的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.15561.pdf">“深度学习”技术的</a>进步可以更容易地发现音高、节奏和语调的模式。<br><br>这就是人工智能目前的奇怪矛盾：尽管这项技术很容易产生偏见，从而疏远用户（语音助手比白人说话者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/applij/advance-article/doi/10.1093/applin/amac066/6901317">更容易错误地识别</a>黑人说话者的话语），但它也可以帮助消除冒泡的较小的疏远感。不断听到机器人错误地说出我的名字是一种数字侮辱，它提醒我，我的设备似乎不是为我而设计的，尽管 Saahil Desai 在印度是一个常见的名字。我的蓝色 iPhone 12 是一块六英寸厚的平板，它比我生命中的任何其他物品都更能容纳<em>我</em>。然而它仍然搞砸了我身份的最基本的事情。<br><br>但机器人能够理解并说出我和你的名字的世界也是一个令人毛骨悚然的世界。 ElevenLabs 所采用的声音克隆技术已被用来制作可信的深度伪造品——粗鲁的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-taylor-swift-fan-generated-deepfakes-misinformation/673596/">泰勒·斯威夫特</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/">乔·罗根和本·夏皮罗辩论</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/"><em>《料理鼠王》</em></a> 、艾玛·沃特森阅读<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs"><em>《我的奋斗》</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs">的一部分</a><em>。</em>当另一端的声音可以像你的亲戚一样说出你的名字时，冒充你认识的人的人工智能骗局就更加可信。<br><br>一旦我清楚地知道我无法击败 ElevenLabs，我就输入了我的中间名 Abhijit。出来的是一团乱七八糟的音节，我永远也骗不了。好吧，好吧：我承认说萨希尔·阿比吉特·德赛实际上很难。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 16:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I Have Cancer. I Can’t Put My Kids First Anymore.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>我的两个孩子将如何度过这次对我的母性和我照顾他们的能力的攻击？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/qur6QzoAVl_0o0pIwGscgsqF_10=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/cancer_motherhood_holly_stapleton/original.jpg" alt="浴缸里的女人" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>霍莉·斯泰普尔顿 (Holly Stapleton) 为《大西洋月刊》</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br>今年二月，距离我40岁生日还有两个月，我的左乳房变得又肿又痛。我把它归咎于所谓的围绝经期这一包罗万象的侮辱。但三月和四月来了又去，我的乳房似乎更糟了。五月到来了，我忙着安排乳房X光检查。我担心最坏的情况发生，但事实证明，进行乳房X光检查比我想象的更难。当我最终预约时，我带了我妹妹来，因为我非常确定出了什么问题。<br><br>令人沮丧的是，事实证明我的担心并没有起到预防作用。放射科医生显得紧张而忧郁。她告诉我们，她“非常担心”我的乳房和淋巴结中的肿块，但医院几周都无法为我提供活检。基本上，我得了癌症，但没有人能告诉我更多关于它的事情。她拍拍我的手臂，就像我是一只不听话的狗一样，然后把我送到走廊另一头的一名执业护士那里，她试图收拾我生活的碎片。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/05/mothers-day-afghanistan-kabul/674045/">阅读：我希望我永远不必学习母性的教训</a><br><br>“我等不及要等两周才能进行活检，”我哭着告诉她。 “我随时随地都可以去。”<br><br>她一直很爱管闲事，让人放心，被键盘分散了注意力，但她停下来抬头看着我。<br><br> “这很有帮助。许多母亲表示，由于孩子的足球或其他原因，她们在某一天或某个时间无法完成任务。”<br><br>我不知道她是否因为我对孩子们的课外活动的冷漠而评判我，或者她是否因为其他母亲而评判我。<i>我</i>评判了他们。作为一名为儿童及其照顾者提供支持的社会工作者，我花了数年的时间向成年人灌输可预测的例行公事在孩子生活中的价值，但实际上：如果这些孩子的母亲去世了，他们去参加足球训练又有什么关系呢？ ？<br><br> “他们的父亲会开车送他们去舞蹈课，”我姐姐干脆利落地告诉护士。 “我们需要进行活检。”<br><br>她说她会看看自己能做些什么。<br><br>我和姐姐离开医院，惊讶地发现我最担心的事情得到了证实，但对诊断或预后几乎一无所知。放射科医生、执业护士和他们的乳房 X 光检查机都在波士顿郊区的一个豪华郊区，我们必须经过一家公文式辅导企业才能到达一家昂贵的咖啡店。我们坐在外面，一个年轻人在两个老人的陪伴下大声不停地谈论她即将从当地一所非常有名望的大学毕业。年长的人根本插不上话。我和姐姐听着，我们因悲伤而哑口无言。我一次又一次地想起那些开车去训练、比赛或公文的母亲们，她们的癌症在她们体内肆虐，不受控制，而她们却在切橙子、拖长曲棍球棒、在 iPad 上加载数学应用程序，并为自己欢呼得声音嘶哑。<br><br>我很害怕知道自己患有癌症，但一无所知，所有这些妇女都推迟了乳房X光检查或活组织检查，甚至推迟了体检，因为她们正忙着为她们希望送走的孩子做出租车。 10年后就读于名牌大学。这位大学生对我不感兴趣的话题大声澄清了她的立场。<br><br>但即使我愤怒不已，我的脑海里仍然充斥着我的孩子们。我的大儿子 10 岁了——长腿，懂事，但仍然被印花布小动物迷住了——而她的弟弟 5 岁：傻乎乎的，圆脸颊，口齿不清，甜蜜地关心，但仍然不确定仙女是否真实存在。想到他们在没有我照顾的情况下存在——没有母亲为他们订购校服，或者劝说他们摆脱心痛，或者包扎他们的伤口，或者在睡前大声朗读<i>夏洛特的网</i>，并为夏洛特的美丽死亡与他们一起哭泣——令人难以忍受且费尽心力。我所能想到的就是他们的脆弱。它消除了我自己的痛苦，我对我的身体和生命的恐惧。<br><br>在接下来的几周里，我得到了活检、肿瘤科医生的帮助，最后得到了诊断和计划：癌症具有侵袭性，但尚未扩散到重要器官或骨骼。肿瘤可能对治疗有反应。我的孩子们可能会留下我，但首先我必须忍受一年的严酷考验：化疗、乳房切除术、每日放射治疗和定期药物治疗。<br><br>我的生活已经崩溃了；我丈夫的额头已经形成了永久的皱纹。两年前，我做了手术；事情发生后，他立即把孩子们带走了，这样我就可以和父亲一起坐在一个安静的房子里，我唯一的任务就是吃饭、睡觉和治疗。我们都知道，在接下来的几个月里，他会给我同样的空间，或者尝试这样做。但我必须一次又一次地接受它。<br><br>我于六月初开始治疗。不久之后，我开始感觉很糟糕。<br><br>化疗会毒害癌症，也会毒害身体：口鼻膜、胃壁、骨髓和关节。我花了很多时间在床上。我的两个孩子来看望我并跳上那张床。有时我会沉迷于此。有时我建议他们走开。我渴望感觉不那么卑鄙，渴望比我所知道的更强烈：它比欲望或保护我的孩子的愿望更强烈。<br><br>我居住的地方普罗维登斯是一个小镇；原来，我女儿朋友的母亲的伴侣从事针灸治疗，专门帮助接受化疗的人。我预约了；唯一有空的时间是我女儿上钢琴课的时候。我送她下车，然后意识到针灸诊所就在她音乐学校的楼下。我躺在桌子上，针灸师正在做他的工作，我花了很长时间才注意到断断续续的钢琴音乐不是来自我旁边柜台上的小型蓝牙扬声器，而是来自楼上。<i>这是我女儿玩的吗？</i>我不这么认为，但我也不能确定；我并不总是全神贯注地关注她在家练习。由于化疗而生病，我错过了上周末她的演奏会。<br><br>为了让针灸“起作用”，你必须“放松”。我并没有放松。我想知道以下问题：<i>是洛拉在我上方玩耍吗？她是否</i><i>因为我错过了演奏会而感到非常难过？</i><i>我的一个朋友和她的女儿走了，给洛拉带来了一束淡粉色的毛茛花。这减轻了我的负罪感，但这对她意味着什么？</i><i>我的女儿现在在玩耍的时候在想我吗？她是在担心我吗？她的担忧会像漏水一样渗透到天花板吗？我的两个孩子将如何度过这次对我的母性和我照顾他们的能力的攻击？我无法为他们提供可预测的白天和夜晚，他们将如何生存？</i>我头顶上的音乐变得令人着迷：我必须知道那是不是我熟悉的女孩在演奏。<br><br>我用手指抚摸着覆盖在我身上的淡绿色床单的边缘。很难不想起裹尸布或太平间的遮盖物。不可能不想起我的女儿。<br><br>就在我开始化疗之前，我的朋友玛格丽特过来坐在我的蓝色沙发上。她给我讲了一个故事——一个警示故事——发生在两年前，当时她正在接受卵巢癌的治疗。她正处于化疗期间的低迷状态，但她的卧室里有一篮子干净的衣服，它执着地看着她——这是照顾和母性的象征，也是一个需要照顾的家庭——所以她把疲劳抛到一边，把衣服叠起来。该死的洗衣服。完成一个篮子花了她几个小时，之后她就被累垮了，不得不小睡一会儿。 “这不值得，”她告诉我。 “但我也这么认为。”<br><br>我惊恐地听着，并向我丈夫重复了这个故事，他的眉头因担忧而皱得更深。他接受了这一切——我们都开始明白，在接下来的几个月里，我不会有多大用处。朋友和亲戚主动提出来帮忙，尽管我们可能曾经表示反对，但我们说，<i>是的，请，非常感谢，你什么时候到达，你能呆多久？</i><br><br> “谁会做……你做的所有事情？”当我解释治疗计划时，一位朋友问我。<br><br> “我不知道，”我说。 “但不会是我。”但正如我所说，我知道我会继续听到洗衣篮的海妖之歌和我女儿的玩耍声。而且我必须捂住耳朵。<br><br>每一天都让我想起自己的脆弱，以及我正在失去或即将失去的一切——我的头发、我的生产力、乳房、身体完整性、生殖功能、我的身体是盟友而不是敌人的信念、我的能力。享受美味的食物并照顾我的孩子，而不会给自己带来风险。我想象着玛格丽特的篮子里装着干净的衣服，我想象着把它展开放置。<br><br>有时，孩子们洗完澡后似乎会吻我道晚安，或者传达一些好消息，我感觉自己就像英国时代作品中一位遥远的母亲。除了我不忙着从伦敦订购连衣裙或处理厚厚的米色信纸上的信件之外；我一动不动地躺在那里，看着又一个男人在<i>跑马地</i>谋杀了另一个女人。在那些时刻，我想知道我是谁。<br><br>为我的孩子们创造和维持稳定、安全和日常生活一直是我成年生活的念珠。我自己生活中的任何剧变——一次搬家、一次死亡、一场流行病——都会影响他们和我，这一想法不仅是我养育孩子的组织原则，也是我生存的组织原则。当我遇到困难时，它让我继续前进。<br><br>我很难放弃照顾孩子们的癌症经历的想法，很难关上卧室的门以防止就寝时间的喧闹，也很难放弃自己的需求并只是休息。持久的治疗和康复已成为我的目标，取代了我最重要的任务是以最好或最优化的方式养育子女的想法。退缩到自己身边，远离我的孩子，感觉就像忘记了我作为母亲所教的一切，或传授给他人的一切，但我看不到其他生存之道。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/motherhood-children-it-goes-so-fast-book/673649/">玛丽·路易丝·凯利：母亲做出的最艰难的决定</a><br><br>在我的第二次针灸预约中，我躺在桌子上并设法专注于我的呼吸；我睡了又睡。<br><br>我的孩子们在这场灾难中的经历——这段痛苦、悲惨的时期——将在他们小小的心灵中留下印记。但我意识到，我现在的任务是在火中游泳。他们会在岸边等待、观察。针灸师悄悄地走进房间，移动针头，上下移动我的四肢。他这样做时什么也没说，而我也沉默了，也许是害怕打破咒语。我想<i>我会从河里给他们飞吻</i>。<i>其他人需要和他们一起站在水边，握住他们的手。</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Joe Lieberman Weighs the Trump Risk]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> No Labels 联合主席表示，第三方选票对 2024 年的特朗普没有帮助。民主党对此表示怀疑。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/cg84lZt1ywrOgleA7CPlzmryEI4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/joe_lieberman/original.jpg" alt="乔·利伯曼" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>克里斯托弗·古德尼/彭博/盖蒂</figcaption></figure>乔·利伯曼想要澄清一件事。这位前康涅狄格州参议员、曾经的副总统候选人上周在电话中告诉我，“我最不想参与的事情就是让唐纳德·特朗普重返椭圆形办公室。”<br><br>民主党人有他们的疑虑。 2006年，康涅狄格州民主党在初选中将利伯曼击败，他以无党派人士身份赢得了第四个参议院任期，自那以后，利伯曼和他的前党派多年来一直交战不休。 2008 年，利伯曼突然解放了，他支持共和党人约翰·麦凯恩而不是巴拉克·奥巴马，并继续粉碎民主党通过《平价医疗法案》制定公共医疗保险计划的梦想。<br><br>他现在是 No Labels 的联合主席，该中间派组织正准备在 2024 年竞选第三方总统候选人，这让民主党人越来越警惕。该组织的领导人表示，他们正在努力让选民免于二元重赛。大多数美国人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/04/25/2024-trump-biden-presidential-rematch">告诉民意调查者</a>他们不希望特朗普和乔·拜登总统之间发生这样的事情。但民主党人和不少共和党人担心，这样的计划可能会导致利伯曼坚称他不愿意看到的事情发生：特朗普重返白宫。 No Labels 自己的民意调查和独立调查都<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/07/12/no-labels-poll-third-party-manchin">显示</a>，一位“温和、独立”的候选人可以获得多达 20% 的普选票，并且从拜登那里获得的支持将多于从特朗普那里获得的支持。如果 2024 年的选举结果与 2020 年的选举结果一样接近（几乎所有政治预言家都相信这一点），那么这可能是决定性的。<br><br> No Labels 已经因推动第三方门票而失去了联合创始人之一威廉·高尔斯顿 (William Galston)。高尔斯顿今年春天<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-may-re-elect-donald-trump-third-party-independent-galston-rematch-f2e7697d">辞职，以抗议</a>此次竞标可能使选举结果向特朗普倾斜。众议院无标签支持的问题解决者核心小组的民主党成员也出于同样的原因否认了这一努力。温和的民主党团体“第三条道路”坚决反对这一想法，一个新的两党团体<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/07/11/gephardt-no-labels-third-party/">正在组建</a>来阻止它。<br><br>目前，利伯曼并没有被吓倒。 “我认为两党人士，尤其是民主党人，都反应过度了，”利伯曼告诉我。 “他们确实应该做得更好，尝试为自己的选票建立支持，并采用一个更接近中心的平台。”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/proportional-representation-house-congress/674627/">阅读：解决两极分化的激进想法</a><br><br>No Labels 由民主党筹款人南希·雅各布森 (Nancy Jacobson) 于 2010 年创立，最初的重点是在奥巴马总统任期内推广中间派政策并打破国会的党派僵局。它于 2017 年成立了问题解决者核心小组，并宣扬了在拜登支持下通过的一些主要两党法案，包括 2021 年基础设施法。它现在正在投入大量资金支持一个想法，即所谓的由一名民主党人和一名共和党人组成的统一选票，这个想法在过去二十年中<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/01/17/bipartisan-presidential-unity-ticket-heal-divided-america-2020-column/2583404002/">反复</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/story/2007/02/unity08-plans-to-field-fusion-ticket-aimed-at-moderates-002657">出现</a>，但从未真正实现。无标签组织的领导人表示，他们要到春季才会决定是否提名候选人，届时他们将评估主要政党的提名人，看看民意调查显示第三方竞标可能产生的影响。到目前为止，他们拒绝讨论他们的实际候选人可能是谁。<br><br> No Labels 援引该组织去年 12 月委托进行的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://roar-assets-auto.rbl.ms/files/52325/HarrisX%20No%20Labels%20-%20Insurance%20Policy%20Data%20-%2030%20March%202023%20-%20VF.pdf">一项大型民意调查</a>，认为第三方选票可以赢得足够多的州（包括一些深红色和深蓝色的州）来赢得选举人团。利伯曼承认，这仍然是一项艰巨的任务。他表示，“无标签”希望潜在的团结票能够发挥“建设性作用”，即使它没有获胜，从而将双方拉回到意识形态中间。例如，他们希望两党之一能够接受昨天发布的“常识” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.commonsensemajority.org/_files/ugd/9f0726_a8092681d4cc40ae8623b98b83d3853d.pdf">政策议程</a>。然而，目前尚不清楚这是否会让拜登或特朗普更受选民欢迎。<br><br>该团体的北极星是已故的罗斯·佩罗，他在 1992 年获得了 19% 的选票，是最后一位获得广泛民众支持的第三方候选人。利伯曼称赞佩罗的努力促使比尔·克林顿总统采取了导致联邦预算平衡的政策；许多共和党人认为，这位得克萨斯州商人让乔治·H·W·布什失去了第二个任期。最近的第三方候选人，例如 2016 年的吉尔·斯坦 (Jill Stein)，虽然获得的支持要少得多，但扮演了更明显的搅局者角色，为共和党赢得了总统选举的胜利。 2000 年阿尔·戈尔 (Al Gore) 的竞选搭档利伯曼 (Lieberman) 非常清楚拉尔夫·纳德 (Ralph Nader) 在那次选举中的影响，当时他从佛罗里达州的民主党选票中夺走了关键选票。<br><br> “当我明年查看数据时，我将非常谨慎地解释它，”利伯曼说。 “如果看起来，尽管我们有目标，但我们可能会无意中造成帮助唐纳德·特朗普连任的真正风险，我将强烈反对运行第三方选票。我认为我代表了“无标签”中的大多数人，包括领导层。”<br><br>然而，尽管利伯曼一直在谈论谨慎，但该组织正在积极为所谓的针对拜登与特朗普复赛的国家“保险政策”奠定基础。 No Labels 正在投入 7000 万美元来确保每个州的选票准入，并且已经在一些重要战场上取得了进展。今天，西弗吉尼亚州参议员乔·曼钦和前犹他州州长乔恩·亨茨曼将在新罕布什尔州正式启动该组织的“常识”议程。曼钦并未排除以无标签竞选总统的可能性，尽管他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/mkraju/status/1679178567756791808">向美国有线电视新闻网坚称</a>，他对这个早期初选州的高调访问并不表明他对这个想法有兴趣。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/11/how-moderates-could-actually-take-control-washington/620599/">马修·伊格莱西亚斯（Matthew Yglesias）和史蒂文·M·泰勒斯（Steven M. Teles）：一个温和的提议</a><br><br>利伯曼清楚地表达了他对特朗普的厌恶，但他对于拜登为何（甚至是否）表现不佳的问题却更加模糊。他一再表示，如果选择是拜登还是特朗普，他会投票给民主党，他深情地谈到了他近 40 年前第一次见到的人，并与他在参议院共事了 20 年。但他仍在寻找更好的选择。我问他支持第三方选票是因为拜登做得不好，还是因为选民<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/biden-approval-rating/">认为</a>他做得不好。 “我认为两者都是，”利伯曼回答道。 “他是一个值得尊敬的人，但他经常因为左派的压力而偏离正常轨道”。这是共和党人经常谈论的话题，也是曼钦时不时提出的抱怨。<br><br>不过，认为拜登过于左倾的看法并不是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/12/democrats-biden-approval-rating/621048/">导致</a>他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/broad-doubts-bidens-age-acuity-spell-republican-opportunity/story?id=99109308#:~:text=President%20Joe%20Biden's%20job%20approval,in%20early%20preferences%20for%202024.">支持率低的</a>原因。事实上，从很多方面来说，拜登都是利伯曼等温和派长期以来一直呼吁支持的那种总统。是的，他签署了两项纯粹通过党派路线投票通过的主要法案（2021年的《美国救援计划法案》和一年后的《通货膨胀削减法案》），但他一再优先考虑与共和党人进行谈判，最近一次<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/05/biden-gop-debt-ceiling-negotiation/674070/">是关于债务上限的谈判</a>。利伯曼称赞拜登的两党基础设施​​法以及他今年春天与众议院议长凯文·麦卡锡达成的预算协议。利伯曼说：“他做了一些重大的事情。”他还赞扬了总统对冠状病毒大流行的初步处理。当我问他拜登在哪些方面过于左倾时，他最初拒绝列出任何问题。然后他提到了“无标签”组织的政策计划，指出其中包括有关枪支和移民的“常识性”建议。<br><br>尽管已经离任十多年，但 81 岁的利伯曼比拜登年长不到一岁。他说，他相信总统无论在身体上还是在认知上都能胜任这份工作，他不愿意要求他下台。但利伯曼温和地建议，这可能是更好的做法。 “我对他再次跑步的决心感到震惊，”他笑着说。 “对他来说，不参选会更容易，他可以带着真正的自豪感退休，并在公共服务领域拥有极其富有成效的职业生涯。”<br><br>利伯曼的回应巧妙地表明了无标签公司的希望，即春天到来时，他们的决定将是一个容易的决定。也许拜登会改变主意并退出，或者特朗普的法律困境最终会说服共和党选民转向其他地方。目前看来，这两种情况都不太可能发生。<br><br>利伯曼和他的盟友可能会认为提名第三方候选人无助于特朗普连任，但这不是他们可以确定的事情。我问利伯曼：如果他如此一心想让特朗普下台，那么冒的风险不是太大了吗？他没有给出明确的答案。 “是的，”他回答道。 “我的意思是，我们拭目以待。”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Most Shocking Aspect of RFK Jr.’s Anti-Semitism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>令人惊讶的不是肯尼迪提出了反犹太阴谋，而是花了这么长时间。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rxpGHPhlsK812tEHTXc5twzmss8=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rfk_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="小罗伯特·RFK" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by The Atlantic.资料来源：杰米·麦卡锡/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>上周，在曼哈顿的一次晚宴上，民主党初选候选人小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪分享了他对冠状病毒本质的直率想法。 “有一种观点认为它是针对种族的，”他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/15/rfk-jr-says-covid-was-ethnically-targeted-to-spare-jews/">在视频中的</a>言论中解释道。 “COVID-19 的目标是攻击白人和黑人。 The people who are most immune are Ashkenazi Jews and Chinese.”肯尼迪补充道，可以肯定的是，“我们不知道它是否是故意针对的。”换句话说，肯尼迪显然认为，这场大流行病是否是由一个阴暗的阴谋集团为了拯救中国和犹太人而策划的，这是一个悬而未决的问题。<br><br>中国至少有 100 万人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/china-million-covid-deaths-communist-party/673177/">死于</a>COVID-19；纽约等地的犹太人非但没有对这种病毒免疫，反而常常被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bklyner.com/editorial-stop-blaming-orthodox-jews-blame-trump-for-brooklyn-covid-spikes/">不公平地指责</a>为传播病毒的罪魁祸首。作为一名曾与冠状病毒作斗争的犹太人，肯尼迪的说法对我来说是新闻。但考虑到消息来源，他们也并不感到意外。这是因为肯尼迪是一个阴谋论者，而阴谋的弧线很短，并且向犹太人倾斜。<br><br>以下只是肯尼迪<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-jr-2024-election-anti-establishment-voters/674588/">观点</a>的一小部分：无线互联网的辐射<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D3OkKer7Ohw">会导致</a>癌症；供水中的化学物质正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/13/politics/robert-kennedy-jr-chemicals-water-children-frogs/index.html">造成性别不安</a>；中央情报局杀害了他的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-interview-david-samuels#:~:text=he%20was%20also%20a%20CIA%20asset">父亲</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/3993563-robert-kennedy-jr-sees-overwhelming-evidence-cia-involved-in-jfk-assassination/">叔叔</a>约翰·F·肯尼迪总统；抗抑郁药<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/robert-kennedy-jr-elon-musk-american-revolution-twitter-spaces-conversation-2023-6">导致了</a>今天的大规模枪击事件；乔治·W·布什 (George W. Bush) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/politics/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-nut-job">窃取了</a>2004 年总统选举的胜利；你手机的 5G 连接是“收集我们的数据并控制我们的行为” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2022/01/23/rfk-jr-compares-pandemic-mandates-to-nazi-germany/">阴谋的一部分</a>。<br><br>从肯尼迪的职业生涯来看，令人惊讶的不是他涉足反犹太主义，而是他花了这么长时间才到达这里。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">之前写过的</a>：<br><br><p>反犹太主义可以说是世界上<a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/texas-synagogue-anti-semitism-conspiracy-theory/621286/">最古老、最持久的</a>阴谋论。它将犹太人描绘成世界政治、经济和社会问题背后幕后操纵的傀儡师。对于那些寻求简单解决生活复杂问题的人来说，这种观点提供了现成的解释——也是敌人。任何寻求社会苦难单一来源的人可能会从普通的阴谋论开始，但很快就会以人云亦云的反犹太思想告终。</p>因为反犹太主义已经产生了几个世纪以来将人类问题归咎于犹太人的材料，所以一个相信有一只看不见的手在操纵世界事务的人最终会发现它属于一个看不见的犹太人。<br><br>因此，在阴谋论边缘流通而不遭遇反犹太主义是不可能的。这就是为什么肯尼迪经常发现自己与那些相信并表达反犹太思想的人在一起。上周，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1678528085258301440">大肆宣传</a>自己与说唱歌手艾斯·库珀(Ice Cube)的会面，艾斯·库珀是一位阴谋论者， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/ice-cube-criticized-anti-semitic-images-conspiracy-theories-9400472/">长期以来</a>一直发表奇怪的反犹太主义推文和歌词。过去，肯尼迪还与仇恨传教士路易斯·法拉罕（Louis Farrakhan）达成了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LouisFarrakhan/status/614862836431392769">共同</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4910041/user-clip-rfk-jr-told-louis-farrakhan-cdc-kill-black-boys">目标</a>，后者经常谴责所谓的犹太人控制媒体和政府。<br><br>肯尼迪最终会回应他的阴谋集团的反犹太主义假设是不可避免的。事实上，他远非第一个走上从阴谋主义到彻底反犹太主义这条老路的人。近年来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/61897999d581bf0020f74c32/why-rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-just-championed-louis-farrakhan/">马乔里·泰勒·格林</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/why-its-become-harder-to-joke-about-anti-semitism/672120/">凯里·欧文</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">埃隆·马斯克</a>等形形色色的人已经从普通的阴谋论发展到反犹太论点。就连肯尼迪的 COVID-19 猜想的内容也不是原创的：几个世纪以来，犹太人一直被指责传播瘟疫，最著名的是欧洲<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/the-black-death">黑死病</a>期间。<br><br>周末，肯尼迪在推特上愤怒地发布了否认和澄清， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1680227322509635595">坚称</a>他的意思只是说新冠病毒“作为针对种族的生物武器的一种概念证明”，而不是“种族效应是故意设计的”，尽管他明确提出他原来的言论中确实有这种可能性。<br><br>肯尼迪本人没有反犹太主义历史，也从未表现出对犹太人的个人偏见。但他的阴谋罗盘确保了他最终会到达这个目的地，因为它只指向一个方向。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:36:04 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/</item></channel></rss>